{"pageid": 1, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@sequential+block@diff_5-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@vertical+block@diff_5-tab6", "text": "The idea behind the previous problem was that immediately differentiating [mathjaxinline]y=x^{m/n}[/mathjaxinline] was hard. But differentiating the _implicit_ function [mathjaxinline]y^n=x^m[/mathjaxinline] was a whole lot easier. This happens any time your function is more simply described implicitly. An implicit function is an equation involving both [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]y[/mathjaxinline] (or any two variables really). You _could_ solve for [mathjaxinline]y[/mathjaxinline] as a function of [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline], but often times, that computation is messy (or impossible). If a function is not implicit, we say that it is explicit.  **Examples**    * [mathjaxinline]y^3=x^2[/mathjaxinline] is implicit.     * [mathjaxinline]y=x^{2/3}[/mathjaxinline] is explicit.     * [mathjaxinline]y^2=x[/mathjaxinline] is an implicit description of the two functions [mathjaxinline]y= \\pm \\sqrt{x}[/mathjaxinline].   Implicit functions", "filename": "diff_5-tab6-text1.html", "title": "Implicit functions"}

{"pageid": 2, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@sequential+block@app_1-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@vertical+block@app_1-tab11", "text": "Suppose that [mathjaxinline]x=a[/mathjaxinline] is a critical point of [mathjaxinline]\\ f[/mathjaxinline], with [mathjaxinline]\\ f'(a) = 0[/mathjaxinline]. {"pageid": 5, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@sequential+block@study-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@vertical+block@study-tab4", "text": "**Definition of One-to-One**  A function [mathjaxinline]\\ f[/mathjaxinline] is **one-to-one** if [mathjaxinline]\\ f(a) \\ne f(b)[/mathjaxinline] whenever [mathjaxinline]a\\ne b[/mathjaxinline]. It is one-to-one if and only if its graph satisfies the horizontal line test (no horizontal line intersects its graph at more than one place).  Definition", "filename": "study-tab4-text7.html", "title": "Definition"}

Dealing with Exponential Indeterminate Forms", "filename": "app_2-tab15-text1.html", "title": "Dealing with Exponential Indeterminate Forms"}

{"pageid": 7, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@sequential+block@study-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@vertical+block@study-tab3", "text": "**The Power Rule**  If [mathjaxinline]n[/mathjaxinline] is any fixed real number, and [mathjaxinline]\\ f(x) = x^n[/mathjaxinline], then [mathjaxinline]\\ f'(x) = n x^{n-1}[/mathjaxinline]. {"pageid": 10, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@sequential+block@study-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@vertical+block@study-tab4", "text": "**The Product Rule**  If [mathjaxinline]h(x) = f(x)g(x)[/mathjaxinline], then  [mathjax]h'(x) = f(x)g'(x)+ g(x)f'(x)[/mathjax]|   ---|---      at all points where the derivatives [mathjaxinline]\\ f'(x)[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]g'(x)[/mathjaxinline] are defined. {"pageid": 11, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@sequential+block@approx_1-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@vertical+block@approx_1-tab15", "text": "[PDF Version](/static/pdf/linapprox2-summary.pdf)   **Linear approximations revisited**  You already know how to take linear approximations. This was the main tool for finding the derivatives of all of the basic functions in the previous unit.  We return again to linear approximations because they are the main tool that we use in finding approximations in science and engineering. Here we develop some more tools for using linear approximations, as well as changing our perspective to use linear approximations to estimate how measurement error perpetuates through a system, and understand the system's sensitivity to small perturbations.  **Linear Approximations near [mathjaxinline]x=0[/mathjaxinline]**  Recall that the linear approximation of a function [mathjaxinline]\\ f(x)[/mathjaxinline] for [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline] near [mathjaxinline]x=0[/mathjaxinline] is given by the formula [mathjaxinline]\\ f(x) \\approx f(0) + f'(0)x[/mathjaxinline]. Find linear approximations of all of the basic functions near [mathjaxinline]x=0[/mathjaxinline]. We are going to be using these formulas a lot! So you may even want to memorize them.  We call the linear approximation the  **linearization** of a function.  **Approximations (likely nonlinear) of compositions**  Suppose that [mathjaxinline]g(x)[/mathjaxinline] is a function such that [mathjaxinline]g(0) =0[/mathjaxinline]. To find an approximation of a function [mathjaxinline]f(g(x))[/mathjaxinline] near [mathjaxinline]x=0[/mathjaxinline], we can take a linear approximation for [mathjaxinline]f(u)[/mathjaxinline] and then substitute [mathjaxinline]g(x)[/mathjaxinline] in for [mathjaxinline]u[/mathjaxinline]. The resulting approximation is likely nonlinear, but it is still an approximation!  Warning: this only works if [mathjaxinline]g(0) = 0[/mathjaxinline].  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle f(u) \\approx f(0) + f'(0)u \\qquad \\Longrightarrow \\qquad f\\left(g(x)\\right) \\approx f(g(0)) + f'(g(0))g(x)[/mathjaxinline] |  | (5.28)   ---|---|---|---       **Linear approximations of products**  To find the linear approximation of a function [mathjaxinline]h(x) = f(x)g(x)[/mathjaxinline] near [mathjaxinline]x=0[/mathjaxinline], it suffices to find a linear approximation for [mathjaxinline]f(x)[/mathjaxinline], find a linear approximation for [mathjaxinline]g(x)[/mathjaxinline], and then the linear approximation for [mathjaxinline]h(x)[/mathjaxinline] is the product of these two approximations where we cancel all of the terms that are quadratic (or higher for more products).  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle h(x)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle f(x)g(x)[/mathjaxinline] |  | (5.29)   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle f(x)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\approx[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle f(0) + f'(0)x[/mathjaxinline] |  | (5.30)   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle g(x)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\approx[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle g(0) + g'(0)x[/mathjaxinline] |  | (5.31)   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle h(x)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\approx[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\left(f(0) + f'(0)x\\right)\\left(g(0) + g'(0)x\\right)[/mathjaxinline] |  | (5.32)   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle f(0)g(0) + \\left(f'(0)g(0) +f(0)g'(0)\\right)x + f'(0)g'(0)x^2[/mathjaxinline] |  | (5.33)   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\approx[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle f(0)g(0) + \\left(f'(0)g(0) +f(0)g'(0)\\right)x[/mathjaxinline] |  | (5.34)  Summary", "filename": "approx_1-tab15-text1.html", "title": "Summary"}

{"pageid": 12, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@sequential+block@der_5-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@vertical+block@der_5-tab4", "text": "Why do we like to use Leibniz notation?  The biggest reason is that it reminds us what the input variable is. The derivative is measuring the instantaneous rate of change of the output variable of a function with respect to the input variable. Sometimes, if there are lots of quantities that have variables representing them, it's easy to lose track of what is what; Leibniz notation helps to remind us.  The following set of questions will help you understand why this is useful.  Why Leibniz notation?", "filename": "der_5-tab4-text1.html", "title": "Why Leibniz notation?"}

{"pageid": 15, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@sequential+block@lim_2-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@vertical+block@lim_2-tab10", "text": "Note: we have not proven all of the following facts, but you should feel free to use them.  The following functions are continuous at _all real numbers_ :    * all polynomials     * [mathjaxinline]\\sqrt[3]{x}[/mathjaxinline]     * [mathjaxinline]|x|[/mathjaxinline]     * [mathjaxinline]\\cos x[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\sin x[/mathjaxinline]     * exponential functions [mathjaxinline]a^x[/mathjaxinline] with base [mathjaxinline]a>0[/mathjaxinline]   The following functions are continuous (or right continuous) _at the specified values_ of [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline]:    * [mathjaxinline]\\sqrt{x}[/mathjaxinline], for [mathjaxinline]x \\geq 0[/mathjaxinline]     * [mathjaxinline]\\tan x[/mathjaxinline], at all [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline] where it is defined     * logarithmic functions [mathjaxinline]\\log _{a} x[/mathjaxinline] with base [mathjaxinline]a>0[/mathjaxinline], for [mathjaxinline]x > 0[/mathjaxinline]   Basic continuous functions", "filename": "lim_2-tab10-text1.html", "title": "Basic continuous functions"}

{"pageid": 16, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@sequential+block@diff_6-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@vertical+block@diff_6-tab16", "text": "**Derivatives of inverse functions using implicit differentiation**  This is another way of finding the derivative of [mathjaxinline]\\theta = \\arcsin x[/mathjaxinline]. The relationship between [mathjaxinline]\\theta[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline] is given by  [mathjax]\\sin \\theta = x.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      Differentiating both sides with respect to [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline] yields:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{d}{dx}\\sin \\theta[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = \\frac{d}{dx}x[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\cos \\theta \\frac{d\\theta }{dx}[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = 1[/mathjaxinline] |  |   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{d\\theta }{dx}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = \\frac{1}{\\cos \\theta }[/mathjaxinline] |  |      We know that  [mathjax]\\cos ^2 \\theta + x^2 = \\cos ^2 \\theta + \\sin ^2 \\theta = 1,[/mathjax]|   ---|---      so [mathjaxinline]\\cos \\theta = \\pm \\sqrt{1-x^2}[/mathjaxinline]. Since [mathjaxinline]\\theta[/mathjaxinline] must lie in [mathjaxinline][-\\pi /2, \\pi /2][/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]\\cos \\theta[/mathjaxinline] is positive. Hence  [mathjax]\\frac{d\\theta }{dx} = \\frac{1}{\\cos \\theta } = \\frac{1}{\\sqrt{1-x^2}}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      We can similarly find the derivative of [mathjaxinline]\\theta = \\arccos x[/mathjaxinline]. The relationship between [mathjaxinline]\\theta[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline] is given by  [mathjax]\\cos \\theta = x.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      Differentiating both sides with respect to [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline] yields:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{d}{dx}\\cos \\theta[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = \\frac{d}{dx}x[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle -\\sin \\theta \\frac{d\\theta }{dx}[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = 1[/mathjaxinline] |  |   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{d\\theta }{dx}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = -\\frac{1}{\\sin \\theta }[/mathjaxinline] |  |      We know that  [mathjax]\\sin ^2 \\theta + x^2 = \\sin ^2 \\theta + \\cos ^2 \\theta = 1,[/mathjax]|   ---|---      so [mathjaxinline]\\sin \\theta = \\pm \\sqrt{1-x^2}[/mathjaxinline]. Since [mathjaxinline]\\theta[/mathjaxinline] must lie in [mathjaxinline][0, \\pi ][/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]\\sin \\theta[/mathjaxinline] is positive. Hence  [mathjax]\\frac{d\\theta }{dx} = -\\frac{1}{\\sin \\theta } = -\\frac{1}{\\sqrt{1-x^2}}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---  Implicit differentiation", "filename": "diff_6-tab16-text2.html", "title": "Implicit differentiation"}

{"pageid": 18, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@sequential+block@study-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@vertical+block@study-tab6", "text": "**Indeterminate Forms**  We call [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac00[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{\\infty }{\\infty }[/mathjaxinline] **indeterminate forms,** because when we run into them in a limit, they require further analysis to determine whether the numerator or denominator wins in the race to 0 or [mathjaxinline]\\infty[/mathjaxinline] respectively, or whether they balance out and reach some other finite limit.  Indeterminate Forms", "filename": "study-tab6-text6.html", "title": "Indeterminate Forms"}

{"pageid": 19, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@sequential+block@der_4-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@vertical+block@der_4-tab6", "text": "So far we've calculated derivatives of the following functions using the limit definition of the derivative.  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle f(x) = x^2[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\rightarrow[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle f'(x) = 2x[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle g(x) = mx + b[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\rightarrow[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle g'(x) = m[/mathjaxinline] |  |   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle h(x) = \\frac{1}{x}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\rightarrow[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle h'(x) = -\\frac{1}{x^2}.[/mathjaxinline] |  |      Now we are going to use these formulas to find derivatives of lots of related functions. One nice thing is that we won't have to use the limit definition for these functions!  Recap", "filename": "der_4-tab6-text1.html", "title": "Recap"}

{"pageid": 20, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@sequential+block@hw3A-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@vertical+block@hw3A-tab1", "text": "**About Part A problems**  Part A problems help you practice the mechanics of calculus. {"pageid": 21, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@sequential+block@lim_2-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@vertical+block@lim_2-tab15", "text": "[PDF Version](/static/pdf/continuity-summary.pdf)   **Definition of continuity at a point**  We say that a function [mathjaxinline]\\ f[/mathjaxinline] is **continuous at a point** [mathjaxinline]x = a[/mathjaxinline] if  [mathjax]\\displaystyle {\\lim _{x\\rightarrow a} f(x) } = f(a).[/mathjax]|   ---|---      In particular, if either [mathjaxinline]\\ f(a)[/mathjaxinline] or [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle {\\lim _{x\\rightarrow a} f(x) }[/mathjaxinline] fails to exist, then [mathjaxinline]\\ f[/mathjaxinline] is discontinuous at [mathjaxinline]a[/mathjaxinline].  We say that a function [mathjaxinline]\\ f[/mathjaxinline] is **right- continuous at a point** [mathjaxinline]x = a[/mathjaxinline] if [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle {\\lim _{x\\rightarrow a^+} f(x) } = f(a)[/mathjaxinline].  We say that a function [mathjaxinline]\\ f[/mathjaxinline] is **left-continuous at a point** [mathjaxinline]x = a[/mathjaxinline] if [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle {\\lim _{x\\rightarrow a^-} f(x) } = f(a)[/mathjaxinline].  **Types of Discontinuities**  It is sometimes useful to classify certain types of discontinuities.  If the left-hand limit [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle {\\lim _{x\\rightarrow a^-} f(x) }[/mathjaxinline] and the right-hand limit [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle {\\lim _{x\\rightarrow a^+} f(x) }[/mathjaxinline] both exist at a point [mathjaxinline]x=a[/mathjaxinline], but they are not equal, then we say that [mathjaxinline]\\ f[/mathjaxinline] has a **jump discontinuity** at [mathjaxinline]x=a[/mathjaxinline].  ![](/static/images/u0lim2_jump.svg)  If the overall limit [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle {\\lim _{x\\rightarrow a} f(x) }[/mathjaxinline] exists (i.e., the left- and right-hand limits agree), but the overall limit does not equal [mathjaxinline]\\ f(a)[/mathjaxinline], then we say that [mathjaxinline]\\ f[/mathjaxinline] has a **removable discontinuity** at [mathjaxinline]x=a[/mathjaxinline].  ![](/static/images/u0lim2_removable.svg)  **Definition of continuous functions**  A function [mathjaxinline]\\ f(x)[/mathjaxinline] is **continuous** if for every point [mathjaxinline]c[/mathjaxinline] in the domain of [mathjaxinline]\\ f(x)[/mathjaxinline], the function [mathjaxinline]\\ f[/mathjaxinline] is continuous at the point [mathjaxinline]x=c[/mathjaxinline].  **Basic Continuous Functions**  Note: we have not proven all of the following facts, but you should feel free to use them.  The following functions are continuous at _all real numbers_ :    * all polynomials     * [mathjaxinline]\\sqrt[3]{x}[/mathjaxinline]     * [mathjaxinline]|x|[/mathjaxinline]     * [mathjaxinline]\\cos x[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\sin x[/mathjaxinline]     * exponential functions [mathjaxinline]a^x[/mathjaxinline] with base [mathjaxinline]a>0[/mathjaxinline]   The following functions are continuous _at the specified values_ of [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline]:    * [mathjaxinline]\\sqrt{x}[/mathjaxinline], for [mathjaxinline]x >0[/mathjaxinline]     * [mathjaxinline]\\tan x[/mathjaxinline], at all [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline] where it is defined     * logarithmic functions [mathjaxinline]\\log _{a} x[/mathjaxinline] with base [mathjaxinline]a>0[/mathjaxinline], for [mathjaxinline]x > 0[/mathjaxinline]   **Limit laws and continuity**  If the functions [mathjaxinline]\\ f[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\ g[/mathjaxinline] are continuous everywhere, then:    * [mathjaxinline]\\ f+g[/mathjaxinline] is continuous everywhere.     * [mathjaxinline]\\ f-g[/mathjaxinline] is continuous everywhere.     * [mathjaxinline]\\ f\\cdot g[/mathjaxinline] is continuous everywhere.     * [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\ \\frac{f}{g}[/mathjaxinline] is continuous where it is defined.   **Intermediate Value Theorem**  If [mathjaxinline]\\ f[/mathjaxinline] is a function which is continuous on the interval [mathjaxinline][a,b][/mathjaxinline], and [mathjaxinline]M[/mathjaxinline] lies between the values of [mathjaxinline]\\ f(a)[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\ f(b)[/mathjaxinline], then there is at least one point [mathjaxinline]c[/mathjaxinline] between [mathjaxinline]a[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]b[/mathjaxinline] such that [mathjaxinline]\\ f(c) = M.[/mathjaxinline]  (A function [mathjaxinline]\\ f[/mathjaxinline] is **continuous on a closed interval** [mathjaxinline][a,b][/mathjaxinline] if it is right-continuous at [mathjaxinline]a[/mathjaxinline], left-continuous at [mathjaxinline]b[/mathjaxinline], and continuous at all points between [mathjaxinline]a[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]b[/mathjaxinline].)  Summary", "filename": "lim_2-tab15-text1.html", "title": "Summary"}

{"pageid": 22, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@sequential+block@der_7-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@vertical+block@der_7-tab4", "text": "The derivative of [mathjaxinline]\\sin x[/mathjaxinline] sure looks a lot like some sort of cosine function. Since the sine function repeats every [mathjaxinline]2\\pi[/mathjaxinline], we would expect its derivative to repeat every [mathjaxinline]2\\pi[/mathjaxinline] as well. {"pageid": 23, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@sequential+block@app_4-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@vertical+block@app_4-tab11", "text": "[PDF Version](/static/pdf/relatedrates-summary.pdf)   **Related Rates Strategy**  To solve related rates problems, it is useful to follow this strategy:    1. {"pageid": 24, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@sequential+block@app_3-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@vertical+block@app_3-tab16", "text": "[PDF Version](/static/pdf/maxmin-summary.pdf)   **The Extreme Value Theorem**  If [mathjaxinline]\\ f[/mathjaxinline] is continuous on a closed interval [mathjaxinline][a,b][/mathjaxinline], then there are points at which [mathjaxinline]\\ f[/mathjaxinline] attains its maximum and its minimum on [mathjaxinline][a,b][/mathjaxinline].  It is important to note that this is only guaranteed if the interval is finite and closed. We will talk about infinite intervals and open intervals a little later.  The proof of this theorem is beyond the scope of this course, so we will not present it here.  **Candidates for Extrema**  We want to find the maximum or minimum value of a continuous function [mathjaxinline]\\ f[/mathjaxinline] on a closed interval [mathjaxinline][a, b][/mathjaxinline]. The Extreme Value Theorem guarantees that they will be attained.  The maximum and minimum can only be attained at critical points or endpoints, so we just need to run through all of those candidates to find the largest and smallest values of [mathjaxinline]\\ f[/mathjaxinline].  Summary", "filename": "app_3-tab16-text1.html", "title": "Summary"}

"text": "[PDF Version](/static/pdf/trig-summary.pdf)   **Definition of significant figures**  The number of _significant figures_ is the count of those digits that carry meaning with regards to precision.  **Examples**    * All non-zero digits are significant \u2013 1235 has 4 significant digits.     * Zeros appearing between nonzero digits are significant \u2013 101 has 3 significant digits.     * Trailing zeros in a number containing a decimal are significant \u2013 32.000 has 5 significant figures.   **Non-examples**    * Trailing zeros in a number with no decimal are _not_ significant \u2013 5400 has 2 significant figures.     * Leading zeros in a decimal number are not significant \u2013 0.0003 has 1 significant figure.     * Extraneous digits introduced in a computation to greater precision than measured data are _not_ significant \u2013 if .25 and .50 are measurements accurate to [mathjaxinline]\\pm[/mathjaxinline].01, then in the product (.25)(.50) = 0.125 the last 5 is _not_ significant.   **Derivative of sine and cosine**  The derivative of of the trig functions are:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\frac{d}{dx} \\sin (x)[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = \\cos (x)[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.6)   ---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\frac{d}{dx} \\cos (x)[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = -\\sin (x)[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.7)   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\frac{d^2}{dx^2} \\sin (x)[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = -\\sin (x)[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.8)   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\frac{d^2}{dx^2} \\cos (x)[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = -\\cos (x)[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.9)  Summary", "filename": "der_7-tab11-text1.html", "title": "Summary"}

{"pageid": 31, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@sequential+block@app_2-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@vertical+block@app_2-tab2", "text": "**Objectives**  At the end of this sequence, and after some practice, you should be able to:    * Use the general strategy for **sketching curves by hand**.     * Use limits to evaluate function values at **discontinuities** and **end points** (including [mathjaxinline]\\pm \\infty[/mathjaxinline]).     * Apply **l'H\u00f4pital's rule** to evaluate limits with **indeterminate forms** : [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac00, \\frac{\\infty }{\\infty }[/mathjaxinline].     * Rearrange limits of other indeterminate forms [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 0\\cdot \\infty , \\infty -\\infty[/mathjaxinline] to be of the form [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac00, \\frac{\\infty }{\\infty }[/mathjaxinline].     * Rearrange limits of the exponential indeterminate forms [mathjaxinline]0^0, 1^{\\infty }, \\infty ^0[/mathjaxinline] by applying [mathjaxinline]e^{\\ln }[/mathjaxinline] to get a standard indeterminate form [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac00, \\frac{\\infty }{\\infty }[/mathjaxinline].     * Use l'H\u00f4pital's rule to **compare the growth rates** of functions at infinity.   **Contents: 18 pages**  13 videos (56 minutes 1x speed) 27 questions  Objectives", "filename": "app_2-tab2-text1.html", "title": "Objectives"}

{"pageid": 38, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@sequential+block@der_2-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@vertical+block@der_2-tab3", "text": "We've seen that we can draw a tangent line. Let's take a moment to think about what tangent lines are not. First, though, let's start with a **bad** way to think about tangent lines. {"pageid": 39, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@sequential+block@der_5-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@vertical+block@der_5-tab8", "text": "[PDF Version](/static/pdf/leibniz-summary.pdf)   **Why Leibniz notation?**  Why do we like to use Leibniz notation?  The biggest reason is that it reminds us what the input variable is. The derivative is measuring the instantaneous rate of change of the output variable of a function with respect to the input variable. Sometimes, if there are lots of quantities that have variables representing them, it's easy to lose track of what is what; Leibniz notation helps to remind us.  **Properties of Leibniz notation**    *  **Units:** If [mathjaxinline]P[/mathjaxinline] has units of pressure, and [mathjaxinline]t[/mathjaxinline] has units of [mathjaxinline]time[/mathjaxinline], then [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{dP}{dt}[/mathjaxinline] has units of pressure per time.     * **Evaluating at points:** If we want to take the derivative at a particular point [mathjaxinline]x = 3[/mathjaxinline], then we use the notation [mathjaxinline]\\left.\\displaystyle \\frac{df}{dx}\\right|_{x=3}[/mathjaxinline]. The bar is read as \u201cevaluated at\".     * **Derivatives act on functions:**      * We can write [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{d(x^2)}{dx}[/mathjaxinline] for the derivative of [mathjaxinline]x^2[/mathjaxinline].       * If a formula is long, we can write [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{d}{dy} \\left(y^3 + 2y^2 \\right).[/mathjaxinline]   Summary", "filename": "der_5-tab8-text1.html", "title": "Summary"}

{"pageid": 40, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@sequential+block@app_3-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@vertical+block@app_3-tab7", "text": "We want to find the maximum or minimum value of a continuous function on a closed interval. The Extreme Value Theorem guarantees that they will be attained. The maximum and minimum can only be attained at critical points or endpoints, so we just need to run through all of those candidates to find the largest and smallest values of [mathjaxinline]\\ f[/mathjaxinline].  We'll walk through an example together!  Where might extrema be?", "filename": "app_3-tab7-text1.html", "title": "Where might extrema be?"}

{"pageid": 41, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@sequential+block@app_1-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@vertical+block@app_1-tab2", "text": "**Objectives**  At the end of this sequence, and after some practice, you should be able to:    * Determine the shape of a function's graph based on information from its derivatives.     * Classify critical points using the First and Second Derivative Tests.   **Contents: 17 pages**  8 videos (29 minutes 1x speed) 23 questions  Graphing and Critical Points", "filename": "app_1-tab2-text1.html", "title": "Graphing and Critical Points"}

{"pageid": 42, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@sequential+block@diff_6-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@vertical+block@diff_6-tab9", "text": "**Domain and range, interval notation**  Recall that the **domain** of a function [mathjaxinline]\\ f[/mathjaxinline] is the set of allowable input values. For instance, the domain of the function [mathjaxinline]\\ f(x) = 1/x[/mathjaxinline] is the set of all non-zero real numbers.  The **range** of [mathjaxinline]\\ f[/mathjaxinline] is the set of all possible output values. For instance, the range of the function [mathjaxinline]g(x) = x^2[/mathjaxinline] is the set of all real numbers that are non-negative.  We often use interval notation to express sets of numbers like domains and ranges. A **closed interval** , denoted [mathjaxinline][a,b][/mathjaxinline], is the set of numbers [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline] such that [mathjaxinline]a \\le x \\le b[/mathjaxinline].  An **open interval** , denoted [mathjaxinline](a,b)[/mathjaxinline], is the set of numbers [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline] such that [mathjaxinline]a < x < b[/mathjaxinline].  One can have a half-open, half-closed interval. For instance, [mathjaxinline][-1, 3)[/mathjaxinline] is the set of numbers [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline] such that [mathjaxinline]-1 \\le x <3[/mathjaxinline]. One can also use [mathjaxinline]\\pm \\infty[/mathjaxinline] as endpoints: [mathjaxinline](-\\infty , 0)[/mathjaxinline] is the set of numbers [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline] such that [mathjaxinline]-\\infty <x < 0[/mathjaxinline] (the set of negative numbers, in other words).  This notation using round parentheses for open intervals is not universal; many mathematicians use reversed square brackets instead. For instance, they would denote the interval [mathjaxinline]3 < x < 7[/mathjaxinline] as [mathjaxinline]]3,7[[/mathjaxinline] rather than [mathjaxinline](3,7)[/mathjaxinline]. In this course, however, we will stick to round parentheses for open intervals.  Domain and range", "filename": "diff_6-tab9-text2.html", "title": "Domain and range"}

{"pageid": 43, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@sequential+block@lim_2-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@vertical+block@lim_2-tab2", "text": "**Objectives**  At the end of this sequence, and after some practice, you should be able to:    * Identify points of **discontinuity**.     * Recognize **continuous and discontinuous functions** graphically and from formulas.     * Use **limit laws** to find limits of sums and products of continuous functions.     * Apply the **Intermediate Value Theorem**.   **Contents: 14 pages**  6 videos (23 minutes 1x speed) 17 questions  How do we compute limits?", "filename": "lim_2-tab2-text1.html", "title": "How do we compute limits?"}

{"pageid": 44, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@sequential+block@approx_1-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@vertical+block@approx_1-tab2", "text": "**products**    **compositions**    **error**     **Objectives**  At the end of this sequence, and after some practice, you should be able to:    * Find **linear approximations** of any function.     * Recognize linearizations of basic functions at 0.     * Find linear approximations of **compositions and products** using basic approximations.     * Use the linear approximation to **estimate error**.   **Contents: 14 pages**  8 videos (32 minutes 1x speed) 23 questions  Objectives", "filename": "approx_1-tab2-text1.html", "title": "Objectives"}

{"pageid": 45, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@sequential+block@study-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@vertical+block@study-tab4", "text": "**Definition of [mathjaxinline]e[/mathjaxinline]**  The base [mathjaxinline]e[/mathjaxinline] is the unique real number so that  [mathjax]\\displaystyle \\frac{d}{dx}e^x = e^x.[/mathjax]| (7.11)   ---|---  Definition of e", "filename": "study-tab4-text15.html", "title": "Definition of e"}

{"pageid": 46, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@sequential+block@edxtutorial-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@vertical+block@edxtutorial-tab2", "text": "Take a moment to familiarize yourself with the main problem types we use in this course. {"pageid": 47, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@sequential+block@der_4-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@vertical+block@der_4-tab19", "text": "[PDF Version](/static/pdf/calculatingderivs-summary.pdf)   **Derivatives of constant multiples**  If [mathjaxinline]g(x) = k\\ f(x)[/mathjaxinline] for some constant [mathjaxinline]k[/mathjaxinline], then  [mathjax]\\displaystyle g'(x) = k\\ f'(x)[/mathjax]|   ---|---      at all points where [mathjaxinline]\\ f[/mathjaxinline] is differentiable.  **Derivatives of sums**  If [mathjaxinline]h(x) = f(x) + g(x)[/mathjaxinline], then  [mathjax]\\displaystyle h'(x) = f'(x) + g'(x)[/mathjax]|   ---|---      at all points where [mathjaxinline]\\ f[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]g[/mathjaxinline] are differentiable.  **Derivatives of differences**  Similarly, if [mathjaxinline]j(x) = f(x) - g(x)[/mathjaxinline], then  [mathjax]\\displaystyle j'(x) = f'(x) - g'(x)[/mathjax]|   ---|---      at all points where [mathjaxinline]\\ f[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]g[/mathjaxinline] are differentiable.  **Derivatives of constant multiples - proof**  Suppose that [mathjaxinline]g(x) = kf(x)[/mathjaxinline] for all [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline], where [mathjaxinline]k[/mathjaxinline] is a constant. We want to prove that [mathjaxinline]g'(x) = kf'(x)[/mathjaxinline] at any point [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline] where [mathjaxinline]\\ f[/mathjaxinline] is differentiable.  We know that  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle g'(x)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = \\lim _{\\Delta x \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{g(x+ \\Delta x) - g(x)}{\\Delta x}[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = \\lim _{\\Delta x \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{kf(x + \\Delta x) - kf(x)}{\\Delta x}[/mathjaxinline] |  |   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = \\lim _{\\Delta x \\rightarrow 0} k\\frac{f(x + \\Delta x) - f(x)}{\\Delta x}[/mathjaxinline] |  |   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = \\lim _{\\Delta x \\rightarrow 0} k \\ \\lim _{\\Delta x \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{f(x + \\Delta x) - f(x)}{\\Delta x}.[/mathjaxinline] |  |      The first limit is just [mathjaxinline]k[/mathjaxinline], and the second limit is the definition of [mathjaxinline]\\ f'(x)[/mathjaxinline]. So we get [mathjaxinline]g'(x) = k f'(x)[/mathjaxinline].  **What is linearity?**  We've seen that differentiation \u201crespects\" addition and multiplication by a constant. That is, if you take a derivative of a sum of functions, you get the same thing as if you differentiated each part, and then added the derivatives. Similarly, if you take the derivative of [mathjaxinline]k[/mathjaxinline] times a function, where [mathjaxinline]k[/mathjaxinline] is a constant, then you get [mathjaxinline]k[/mathjaxinline] times the derivative of the original function.  Respecting addition and constant multiplication in this way is called \u201clinearity,\" and it is an important property of the derivative operation!  **The Power Rule**  If [mathjaxinline]n[/mathjaxinline] is any fixed number, and [mathjaxinline]\\ f(x) = x^n[/mathjaxinline], then [mathjaxinline]\\ f'(x) = n x^{n-1}[/mathjaxinline].  Summary", "filename": "der_4-tab19-text1.html", "title": "Summary"}

{"pageid": 48, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@sequential+block@diff_5-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@vertical+block@diff_5-tab5", "text": "**Note on video:** In the video above, we assume that [mathjaxinline]n \\neq 0[/mathjaxinline] so that the quotient is defined, and [mathjaxinline]n\\neq 1[/mathjaxinline] so that the quotient is nontrivial.  Note", "filename": "diff_5-tab5-text1.html", "title": "Note"}

{"pageid": 49, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@sequential+block@study-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@vertical+block@study-tab6", "text": "**L'Hospital's Rule Version 1: Indeterminate form 0/0**  If  [mathjax]\\begin{array}{l} \\displaystyle f(x) \\rightarrow 0\\\\\\ \\displaystyle g(x) \\rightarrow 0 \\end{array} \\quad \\textrm{ as } x \\rightarrow a,[/mathjax]|   ---|---      and the functions [mathjaxinline]\\ f[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]g[/mathjaxinline] are differentiable near the point [mathjaxinline]x=a[/mathjaxinline], then limit  [mathjax]\\displaystyle \\lim _{x \\rightarrow a} \\frac{f(x)}{g(x)} = \\lim _{x \\rightarrow a} \\frac{f'(x)}{g'(x)}[/mathjax]| (7.19)   ---|---      provided that and the right hand limit exists or is [mathjaxinline]\\pm \\infty[/mathjaxinline].  If  [mathjax]\\begin{array}{l} \\displaystyle f(x) \\rightarrow \\pm \\infty \\\\\\ \\displaystyle g(x) \\rightarrow \\pm \\infty \\end{array} \\quad \\textrm{ as } x \\rightarrow a,[/mathjax]|   ---|---      and the functions [mathjaxinline]\\ f[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]g[/mathjaxinline] are differentiable near the point [mathjaxinline]x=a[/mathjaxinline], then limit  [mathjax]\\displaystyle \\lim _{x \\rightarrow a} \\frac{f(x)}{g(x)} = \\lim _{x \\rightarrow a} \\frac{f'(x)}{g'(x)}[/mathjax]| (7.20)   ---|---      provided that and the right hand limit exists or is [mathjaxinline]\\pm \\infty[/mathjaxinline].  Note that    * We can replace [mathjaxinline]a[/mathjaxinline] with [mathjaxinline]a^+[/mathjaxinline] or [mathjaxinline]a^-[/mathjaxinline] and the results (versions 1 and 2) still hold.     * We can replace [mathjaxinline]a[/mathjaxinline] with [mathjaxinline]\\pm \\infty[/mathjaxinline], and the results (versions 1 and 2) still hold.   **Other indeterminate forms**  Other indeterminate forms [mathjaxinline]0\\cdot \\infty[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]\\infty - \\infty[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]0^0[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]1^{\\infty }[/mathjaxinline], and [mathjaxinline]\\infty ^{0}[/mathjaxinline] should be rearranged to be of the form [mathjaxinline]0/0[/mathjaxinline] or [mathjaxinline]\\infty /\\infty[/mathjaxinline] in order to apply l'H\u00f4pital's rule.  L'Hospital's Rule", "filename": "study-tab6-text7.html", "title": "L'Hospital's Rule"}

{"pageid": 50, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@sequential+block@approx_1-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@vertical+block@approx_1-tab9", "text": "**Estimate of the height**  Here is a diagram of the measurements we just carried out.  ![See table below.](/static/images/greenbld_diagram.svg)  The height [mathjaxinline]y[/mathjaxinline] of the Green building is given by  [mathjax]y = h+x\\tan (\\theta ).[/mathjax]|   ---|---      Below is a table of the measurements made, as well as the error in each term.  Quantity |  Variable |  Measurement |  Error   ---|---|---|---   Height to Jen's eyeball |  h |  4.9 feet |  [mathjaxinline]\\pm [/mathjaxinline] .01 feet   Distance to Green Building |  x|  175 feet |  [mathjaxinline]\\pm [/mathjaxinline] 3 feet   Angle |  [mathjaxinline]\\theta [/mathjaxinline]|  57 degrees | [mathjaxinline]\\pm [/mathjaxinline] 3 degrees      Where is the error coming from?    * The error in the measurement of Jen's height comes from rounding error and inherent error in using a tape measure to enough accuracy.     * The error in the distance to the Green building is coming from a few places: error in the actual length of the rope which may differ by a few inches, error in our walking in a perfectly straight line as we measure, and error coming from the fact that the rope is stretching when we pull on it, lengthening the rope. So in fact, we expect our measurement is likely an overestimate.     * The error in the angle is coming from wind and the string not hanging straight down, error in the construction of the device, and error in holding the device to read the measurement.   Measurements", "filename": "approx_1-tab9-text1.html", "title": "Measurements"}

{"pageid": 51, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@sequential+block@der_7-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@vertical+block@der_7-tab5", "text": "We found that  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\frac{d \\ \\sin (x)}{dx}[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =\\quad \\displaystyle \\lim _{\\Delta x \\to 0} \\left( \\sin (x)\\left(\\frac{\\cos (\\Delta x) - 1}{\\Delta x}\\right) + \\cos (x)\\left( \\frac{\\sin (\\Delta x)}{\\Delta x}\\right) \\right)[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = \\quad \\sin (x)\\left( \\lim _{\\Delta x \\to 0} \\frac{\\cos (\\Delta x) - 1}{\\Delta x}\\right) + \\cos (x)\\left(\\lim _{\\Delta x \\to 0} \\frac{\\sin (\\Delta x)}{\\Delta x}\\right)[/mathjaxinline] |  |      We've identified these limits as the derivatives of [mathjaxinline]\\cos[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\sin[/mathjaxinline] at zero respectively. This reduces our problem! To find the derivative of [mathjaxinline]\\sin[/mathjaxinline] everywhere, it is enough to find the derivatives [mathjaxinline]\\sin '(0)[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\cos '(0)[/mathjaxinline].  Derivative of sine", "filename": "der_7-tab5-text1.html", "title": "Derivative of sine"}

{"pageid": 52, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@sequential+block@study-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@vertical+block@study-tab4", "text": "**The derivative of the natural logarithm**  Our collection of basic functions that we can differentiate now has one more entry:  [mathjax]\\frac{d}{dx} \\ln x = \\frac{1}{x}[/mathjax]|   ---|---  The derivative of the natural logarithm", "filename": "study-tab4-text18.html", "title": "The derivative of the natural logarithm"}

{"pageid": 53, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@sequential+block@diff_2-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@vertical+block@diff_2-tab8", "text": "If [mathjaxinline]h(x) = f(x)g(x)[/mathjaxinline], then  [mathjax]h'(x) = f(x)g'(x)+ g(x)f'(x)[/mathjax]|   ---|---      at all points where the derivatives [mathjaxinline]\\ f'(x)[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]g'(x)[/mathjaxinline] are defined.  The Product Rule", "filename": "diff_2-tab8-text1.html", "title": "The Product Rule"}

{"pageid": 54, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@sequential+block@der_7-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@vertical+block@der_7-tab9", "text": "The number of _significant figures_ is the count of those digits that carry meaning with regards to precision.  **Examples**    * All non-zero digits are significant \u2013 1235 has 4 significant digits.     * Zeros appearing between nonzero digits are significant \u2013 101 has 3 significant digits.     * Trailing zeros in a number containing a decimal are significant \u2013 32.000 has 5 significant figures.   **Non-examples**    * Trailing zeros in a number with no decimal are _not_ significant \u2013 5400 has 2 significant figures.     * Leading zeros in a decimal number are not significant \u2013 0.0003 has 1 significant figure.     * Extraneous digits introduced in a computation to greater precision than measured data are _not_ significant \u2013 if .25 and .50 are measurements accurate to [mathjaxinline]\\pm[/mathjaxinline].01, then in the product (.25)(.50) = 0.125 the last 5 is _not_ significant.   Definition of significant figures", "filename": "der_7-tab9-text1.html", "title": "Definition of significant figures"}

{"pageid": 56, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@sequential+block@approx_2-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@vertical+block@approx_2-tab16", "text": "[PDF Version](/static/pdf/quadapprox-summary.pdf)   **Best fit quadratic**  The best fit quadratic to a function [mathjaxinline]\\ f(x)[/mathjaxinline] at the point [mathjaxinline]x=0[/mathjaxinline] is the quadratic function [mathjaxinline]q(x)[/mathjaxinline] whose value agrees with the value of [mathjaxinline]\\ f[/mathjaxinline] at [mathjaxinline]x=0[/mathjaxinline], and whose first and second derivatives agree with the first and second derivatives of [mathjaxinline]\\ f[/mathjaxinline] at [mathjaxinline]x=0[/mathjaxinline], i.e.:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle f(0)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle q(0)[/mathjaxinline] |  | (5.49)   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle f'(0)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle q'(0)[/mathjaxinline] |  | (5.50)   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle f^{\\prime \\prime }(0)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle q^{\\prime \\prime }(0)[/mathjaxinline] |  | (5.51)       **Quadratic Approximation**  The **quadratic approximation** near [mathjaxinline]x=a[/mathjaxinline] is the **best fit parabola** to [mathjaxinline]\\ f[/mathjaxinline] at the point [mathjaxinline]x=a[/mathjaxinline].  The formula for the quadratic approximation of a function [mathjaxinline]\\ f[/mathjaxinline] near a point [mathjaxinline]x=a[/mathjaxinline] is  [mathjax]\\displaystyle f(x) \\approx f(a) + f'(a)(x-a) + \\frac{f^{\\prime \\prime }(a)}{2}(x-a)^2.[/mathjax]| (5.52)   ---|---      When [mathjaxinline]a=0[/mathjaxinline], this quadratic approximation becomes  [mathjax]\\displaystyle f(x) \\approx f(0) + f'(0)x + \\frac{f^{\\prime \\prime }(0)}{2}x^2.[/mathjax]| (5.53)   ---|---       **Big-O notation**  A function [mathjaxinline]\\ f(x)[/mathjaxinline] is on the order [mathjaxinline]x^n[/mathjaxinline] near [mathjaxinline]x=0[/mathjaxinline], which is denoted using big \u201cO\" notation as [mathjaxinline]\\ f(x) = O(x^n)[/mathjaxinline] near [mathjaxinline]x=0[/mathjaxinline], if [mathjaxinline]\\left|f(x)\\right| \\leq k x^n[/mathjaxinline].  **Library of quadratic approximations**  Near zero: [mathjaxinline]\\ \\displaystyle f(x) \\approx f(0) + f'(0)x + \\frac{f^{\\prime \\prime }(0)}{2}x^2[/mathjaxinline].    * [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle {e^x = 1 + x + \\frac{x^2}{2} + O\\left(x^3\\right)}[/mathjaxinline]     * [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle {\\sin (x) = x + O\\left(x^3\\right)}[/mathjaxinline]     * [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle {\\cos (x) = 1- \\frac{x^2}{2} + O\\left(x^3\\right)}[/mathjaxinline]     * [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle {\\ln (1+x) = x- \\frac{x^2}{2} + O\\left(x^3\\right)}[/mathjaxinline]     * [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle {(1+x)^r = 1 + rx + \\frac{r(r-1)}{2}x^2 + O\\left(x^3\\right)}[/mathjaxinline]   Summary", "filename": "approx_2-tab16-text1.html", "title": "Summary"}

{"pageid": 57, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@sequential+block@diff_7-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@vertical+block@diff_7-tab7", "text": "The base [mathjaxinline]e[/mathjaxinline] is the unique real number so that [mathjaxinline]M(e) = \\displaystyle \\left.\\frac{d}{dx} e^x\\right|_{x=0} = 1[/mathjaxinline]. Then  [mathjax]\\displaystyle \\frac{d}{dx}e^x = e^x.[/mathjax]| (4.35)   ---|---  Definition of e", "filename": "diff_7-tab7-text1.html", "title": "Definition of e"}

{"pageid": 59, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@sequential+block@der_1-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@vertical+block@der_1-tab9", "text": "The **derivative** of a function [mathjaxinline]\\ f(x)[/mathjaxinline] at a point [mathjaxinline]x = a[/mathjaxinline] is defined to be  [mathjax]\\displaystyle f'(a) = \\lim _{b\\rightarrow a} \\frac{f(b) - f(a)}{b-a}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      ###  Alternative definition  This alternative definition is also common.  The **derivative** of a function [mathjaxinline]\\ f(x)[/mathjaxinline] at a point [mathjaxinline]x = a[/mathjaxinline] is defined to be  [mathjax]\\displaystyle f'(a) = \\lim _{h\\rightarrow 0} \\frac{f(a+h) - f(a)}{h}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      [Show](javascript: {return false;})  Definition of the derivative", "filename": "der_1-tab9-text1.html", "title": "Definition of the derivative"}

{"pageid": 60, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@sequential+block@app_1-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@vertical+block@app_1-tab13", "text": "An **inflection point** is a point where the concavity of the function changes. That is the second derivative [mathjaxinline]f^{\\prime \\prime }(x)[/mathjaxinline] changes sign\u2014 [mathjaxinline]f^{\\prime \\prime }(x) > 0[/mathjaxinline] just to the left of [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]f^{\\prime \\prime }(x) < 0[/mathjaxinline] just to the right of [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline] (or vice versa).  Definition of Inflection Point", "filename": "app_1-tab13-text1.html", "title": "Definition of Inflection Point"}

{"pageid": 61, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@sequential+block@der_5-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@vertical+block@der_5-tab2", "text": "[mathjaxinline]f'(x)[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{df}{dx}[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{dy}{dx}[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{d}{dx}f[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{d}{dx}y[/mathjaxinline]   ---|---|---|---|---      **Objectives**  At the end of this sequence, and after some practice, you should be able to:    * Understand the rationales for **Leibniz** notation.     * Draw **differential elements**.     * Be able to use Leibniz notation appropriately.   **Contents: 7 pages**  3 videos (7 minutes 1x speed) 10 questions  Objectives", "filename": "der_5-tab2-text1.html", "title": "Objectives"}

{"pageid": 62, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@sequential+block@study-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@vertical+block@study-tab2", "text": "**Definition of the Limit**   **The Limit in Words**  If a function [mathjaxinline]f(x)[/mathjaxinline] approaches some value [mathjaxinline]L[/mathjaxinline] as [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline] approaches [mathjaxinline]a[/mathjaxinline] from _both the right and the left_ , then **the limit** of [mathjaxinline]f(x)[/mathjaxinline] exists and equals [mathjaxinline]L[/mathjaxinline].  **The Limit in Symbols**  If  [mathjax]\\displaystyle {\\lim _{x\\rightarrow a^+} f(x)} = \\displaystyle {\\lim _{x\\rightarrow a^-} f(x)} = L[/mathjax]|   ---|---      then  [mathjax]\\displaystyle {\\lim _{x\\rightarrow a} f(x) = L}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      Alternatively,  [mathjax]f(x) \\rightarrow L \\quad \\mathrm{as} \\quad x\\rightarrow a.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      Remember that [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline] is approaching [mathjaxinline]a[/mathjaxinline] but does not equal [mathjaxinline]a[/mathjaxinline].  ###  Formal definition of limit  Formally, the statement [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle {\\lim _{x\\rightarrow a} f(x) = L}[/mathjaxinline] is defined as:      For all [mathjaxinline]\\varepsilon >0,[/mathjaxinline] there exists some [mathjaxinline]\\delta > 0[/mathjaxinline] such that if [mathjaxinline]0 < |x-a| < \\delta ,[/mathjaxinline] then [mathjaxinline]|f(x)-L| < \\varepsilon .[/mathjaxinline]      As is traditional, we use the Greek letters [mathjaxinline]\\varepsilon[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\delta[/mathjaxinline].  Here is how one might understand that statement. The distance between two numbers [mathjaxinline]y[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]z[/mathjaxinline] is given by [mathjaxinline]|y-z|[/mathjaxinline]. Thus, the very last part of the definition is saying that the distance from [mathjaxinline]f(x)[/mathjaxinline] to [mathjaxinline]L[/mathjaxinline] is less than [mathjaxinline]\\varepsilon[/mathjaxinline]; one should think of [mathjaxinline]\\varepsilon[/mathjaxinline] as representing a small distance. This close distance occurs if [mathjaxinline]0<|x-a|<\\delta[/mathjaxinline]; that is, if [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline] is within some distance [mathjaxinline]\\delta[/mathjaxinline] from [mathjaxinline]a[/mathjaxinline], but not necessarily if that distance is 0 (we don't care about [mathjaxinline]x = a[/mathjaxinline] itself).  The \"for all\" and \"there exists\" clauses have to do with how small these distances need to get. We want [mathjaxinline]f(x)[/mathjaxinline] to eventually get arbitrarily close to [mathjaxinline]L[/mathjaxinline], so this statement needs to be satisfied no matter how small [mathjaxinline]\\varepsilon[/mathjaxinline] gets. Given any choice of [mathjaxinline]\\varepsilon[/mathjaxinline], we can satisfy the condition [mathjaxinline]|f(x) - L | < \\varepsilon[/mathjaxinline] as long as [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline] gets close enough to [mathjaxinline]a[/mathjaxinline]; the proximity required is measured by [mathjaxinline]\\delta[/mathjaxinline].  [Show](javascript: {return false;})  Definition of the Limit", "filename": "study-tab2-text2.html", "title": "Definition of the Limit"}

{"pageid": 63, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@sequential+block@study-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@vertical+block@study-tab6", "text": "**The Second Derivative Test**  Suppose that [mathjaxinline]x=a[/mathjaxinline] is a critical point of [mathjaxinline]\\ f[/mathjaxinline], with [mathjaxinline]\\ f'(a) = 0[/mathjaxinline].  If [mathjaxinline]\\ f^{\\prime \\prime }(a) > 0[/mathjaxinline], then [mathjaxinline]\\ f[/mathjaxinline] has a local minimum at [mathjaxinline]x=a[/mathjaxinline]. | ![](/static/images/u4app1_test4.svg)   ---|---   If [mathjaxinline]\\ f^{\\prime \\prime }(a) < 0[/mathjaxinline], then [mathjaxinline]\\ f[/mathjaxinline] has a local maximum at [mathjaxinline]x=a[/mathjaxinline]. | ![](/static/images/u4app1_test5.svg)   If [mathjaxinline]\\ f^{\\prime \\prime }(a) = 0[/mathjaxinline], or does not exist, then the test is inconclusive \u2014 there might be a local maximum, or a local minimum, or neither. |  The Second Derivative Test", "filename": "study-tab6-text3.html", "title": "The Second Derivative Test"}

{"pageid": 64, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@sequential+block@study-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@vertical+block@study-tab2", "text": "**Definition of Continuous at a Point**  We say that a function [mathjaxinline]\\ f[/mathjaxinline] is **continuous at a point** [mathjaxinline]x = a[/mathjaxinline] if  [mathjax]\\displaystyle {\\lim _{x\\rightarrow a} f(x) } = f(a).[/mathjax]|   ---|---      In particular, if either [mathjaxinline]\\ f(a)[/mathjaxinline] or [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle {\\lim _{x\\rightarrow a} f(x) }[/mathjaxinline] fails to exist, then [mathjaxinline]\\ f[/mathjaxinline] is discontinuous at [mathjaxinline]a[/mathjaxinline].  We say that a function [mathjaxinline]\\ f[/mathjaxinline] is **right- continuous at a point** [mathjaxinline]x = a[/mathjaxinline] if [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle {\\lim _{x\\rightarrow a^+} f(x) } = f(a)[/mathjaxinline].  We say that a function [mathjaxinline]\\ f[/mathjaxinline] is **left-continuous at a point** [mathjaxinline]x = a[/mathjaxinline] if [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle {\\lim _{x\\rightarrow a^-} f(x) } = f(a)[/mathjaxinline].  It is sometimes useful to classify certain types of discontinuities.  If the left-hand limit [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle {\\lim _{x\\rightarrow a^-} f(x) }[/mathjaxinline] and the right-hand limit [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle {\\lim _{x\\rightarrow a^+} f(x) }[/mathjaxinline] both exist at a point [mathjaxinline]x=a[/mathjaxinline], but they are not equal, then we say that [mathjaxinline]\\ f[/mathjaxinline] has a **jump discontinuity** at [mathjaxinline]x=a[/mathjaxinline].  ![](/static/images/u0lim2_jump.svg)  If the overall limit [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle {\\lim _{x\\rightarrow a} f(x) }[/mathjaxinline] exists (i.e., the left- and right-hand limits agree), but the overall limit does not equal [mathjaxinline]\\ f(a)[/mathjaxinline], then we say that [mathjaxinline]\\ f[/mathjaxinline] has a **removable discontinuity** at [mathjaxinline]x=a[/mathjaxinline].  ![](/static/images/u0lim2_removable.svg)  Definition of Continuous at a Point", "filename": "study-tab2-text4.html", "title": "Definition of Continuous at a Point"}

{"pageid": 65, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@sequential+block@der_6-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@vertical+block@der_6-tab4", "text": "The second derivative of a function [mathjaxinline]\\ f(x)[/mathjaxinline] is the first derivative of [mathjaxinline]\\ f'(x)[/mathjaxinline], and is denoted by [mathjaxinline]f^{\\prime \\prime }(x)[/mathjaxinline] or [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{d^2f}{dx^2}[/mathjaxinline].  Second derivative", "filename": "der_6-tab4-text1.html", "title": "Second derivative"}

{"pageid": 66, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@sequential+block@study-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@vertical+block@study-tab2", "text": "**The Limit Laws:**  Suppose [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle {\\lim _{x\\rightarrow a} f(x) = L}, \\qquad \\displaystyle {\\lim _{x\\rightarrow a} g(x) = M}.[/mathjaxinline]  Then we get the following Limit Laws:  Limit Law for Addition: |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle {\\lim _{x\\rightarrow a} \\left[f(x)+g(x)\\right] }[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]=[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]L+M[/mathjaxinline]   ---|---|---|---   Limit Law for Subtraction: |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle {\\lim _{x\\rightarrow a} \\left[f(x)-g(x)\\right] }[/mathjaxinline]| [mathjaxinline]=[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]L-M[/mathjaxinline]   Limit Law for Multiplication: |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle {\\lim _{x\\rightarrow a} \\left[f(x)\\cdot g(x)\\right] }[/mathjaxinline]| [mathjaxinline]=[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]L\\cdot M.[/mathjaxinline]      We also have part of the Limit Law for Division: **Limit Law for Division**  If [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle {\\lim _{x\\rightarrow a} f(x) = L}[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle {\\lim _{x\\rightarrow a} g(x) = M},[/mathjaxinline] then:    * If [mathjaxinline]M \\ne 0,[/mathjaxinline] then [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle { \\lim _{x\\rightarrow a} \\frac{f(x)}{g(x)} = \\frac{L}{M}}[/mathjaxinline].     * If [mathjaxinline]M = 0[/mathjaxinline] but [mathjaxinline]L \\ne 0,[/mathjaxinline] then [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle {\\lim _{x\\rightarrow a} \\frac{f(x)}{g(x)}}[/mathjaxinline] does not exist.     * If both [mathjaxinline]M = 0[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]L = 0,[/mathjaxinline] then [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle {\\lim _{x\\rightarrow a} \\frac{f(x)}{g(x)}}[/mathjaxinline] might exist, or it might not exist. More work is necessary to determine whether the last type of limit exists, and what it is if it does exist.   Limit Laws Summary", "filename": "study-tab2-text3.html", "title": "Limit Laws Summary"}

{"pageid": 67, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@sequential+block@diff_5-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@vertical+block@diff_5-tab2", "text": "**What functions can we differentiate so far?**  powers of [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline]   polynomials   trigonometric functions   products of basic functions   quotients of basic functions   compositions of basic functions     **Objectives**  At the end of this sequence, and after some practice, you should be able to:    * Recognize **implicit functions**.     * **Apply the chain rule** to differentiate implicit functions.     * Understand why the **power rule for fractional powers** holds:   [mathjax]\\displaystyle {\\frac{d}{dx}x^{m/n} = (m/n)x^{m/n-1}}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---    **Contents: 10 pages**  5 videos (23 minutes 1x speed) 14 questions  What functions can we differentiate?", "filename": "diff_5-tab2-text1.html", "title": "What functions can we differentiate?"}

{"pageid": 68, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@sequential+block@study-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@vertical+block@study-tab4", "text": "**Differentiating Exponential Functions with other Bases**  We can finally identify our mystery number, and differentiate exponential functions with any base.  For any positive constant [mathjaxinline]a[/mathjaxinline],  [mathjax]\\frac{d}{dx} a^x = a^x \\ln a.[/mathjax]|   ---|---  Differentiating Exponential Functions with other Bases", "filename": "study-tab4-text16.html", "title": "Differentiating Exponential Functions with other Bases"}

{"pageid": 69, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@sequential+block@study-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@vertical+block@study-tab2", "text": "**Intermediate Value Theorem**  If [mathjaxinline]\\ f[/mathjaxinline] is a function which is continuous on the interval [mathjaxinline][a,b][/mathjaxinline], and [mathjaxinline]M[/mathjaxinline] lies between the values of [mathjaxinline]\\ f(a)[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\ f(b)[/mathjaxinline], then there is at least one point [mathjaxinline]c[/mathjaxinline] between [mathjaxinline]a[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]b[/mathjaxinline] such that [mathjaxinline]\\ f(c) = M.[/mathjaxinline]  (A function [mathjaxinline]\\ f[/mathjaxinline] is **continuous on a closed interval** [mathjaxinline][a,b][/mathjaxinline] if it is right-continuous at [mathjaxinline]a[/mathjaxinline], left-continuous at [mathjaxinline]b[/mathjaxinline], and continuous at all points between [mathjaxinline]a[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]b[/mathjaxinline].)  Intermediate Value Theorem", "filename": "study-tab2-text6.html", "title": "Intermediate Value Theorem"}

{"pageid": 70, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@sequential+block@app_2-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@vertical+block@app_2-tab8", "text": "**l'H\u00f4pital's Rule Version 1: Indeterminate form [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac00[/mathjaxinline]**  If  [mathjax]\\begin{array}{l} \\displaystyle f(x) \\rightarrow 0\\\\\\ \\displaystyle g(x) \\rightarrow 0 \\end{array} \\quad \\text{ as } x \\rightarrow a,[/mathjax]|   ---|---      and the functions [mathjaxinline]\\ f[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]g[/mathjaxinline] are differentiable near the point [mathjaxinline]x=a[/mathjaxinline], then limit  [mathjax]\\displaystyle \\lim _{x \\rightarrow a} \\frac{f(x)}{g(x)} = \\lim _{x \\rightarrow a} \\frac{f'(x)}{g'(x)}[/mathjax]| (6.13)   ---|---      provided that the limit on the right hand side of the equation exists or is [mathjaxinline]\\pm \\infty[/mathjaxinline].  **l'H\u00f4pital's Rule Version 2: Indeterminate form [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{\\infty }{\\infty }[/mathjaxinline]**  If  [mathjax]\\begin{array}{l} \\displaystyle f(x) \\rightarrow \\pm \\infty \\\\\\ \\displaystyle g(x) \\rightarrow \\pm \\infty \\end{array} \\quad \\text{ as } x \\rightarrow a,[/mathjax]|   ---|---      and the functions [mathjaxinline]\\ f[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]g[/mathjaxinline] are differentiable near the point [mathjaxinline]x=a[/mathjaxinline], then limit  [mathjax]\\displaystyle \\lim _{x \\rightarrow a} \\frac{f(x)}{g(x)} = \\lim _{x \\rightarrow a} \\frac{f'(x)}{g'(x)}[/mathjax]| (6.14)   ---|---      provided that the right hand limit exists or is [mathjaxinline]\\pm \\infty[/mathjaxinline].  Note that    * We can replace [mathjaxinline]a[/mathjaxinline] with [mathjaxinline]a^+[/mathjaxinline] or [mathjaxinline]a^-[/mathjaxinline] and the results (versions 1 and 2) still hold.     * We can replace [mathjaxinline]a[/mathjaxinline] with [mathjaxinline]\\pm \\infty[/mathjaxinline], and the results (versions 1 and 2) still hold.   l'Hospital's Rule", "filename": "app_2-tab8-text1.html", "title": "l'Hospital's Rule"}

{"pageid": 73, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@sequential+block@der_4-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@vertical+block@der_4-tab3", "text": "In the last sequence, you learned how to sketch the graph of [mathjaxinline]\\ f'[/mathjaxinline] given the graph of [mathjaxinline]\\ f[/mathjaxinline]. {"pageid": 74, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@sequential+block@der_2-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@vertical+block@der_2-tab8", "text": "Now, when we defined the derivative of [mathjaxinline]\\ f[/mathjaxinline] at [mathjaxinline]a[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]\\ f'(a)[/mathjaxinline], we took the limit of [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{f(b)-f(a)}{b-a}[/mathjaxinline] as [mathjaxinline]b[/mathjaxinline] approached [mathjaxinline]a[/mathjaxinline]. We've just seen that this quantity is the slope of the secant line that connects the points [mathjaxinline](a,f(a))[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline](b,f(b))[/mathjaxinline]. {"pageid": 86, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@sequential+block@study-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@vertical+block@study-tab5", "text": "**Linear Approximations of basic functions near 0**  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle (1+x)^r \\approx 1 + rx[/mathjaxinline]   [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\sin (x) \\approx \\sin (0) + \\cos (0)x = x[/mathjaxinline]   [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\cos (x) \\approx \\cos (0) - \\sin (0)x = 1[/mathjaxinline]   [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle e^x \\approx e^0 + e^0 x = 1 + x[/mathjaxinline]   [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\ln (1+x) \\approx \\ln (1+0) + \\frac{1}{1+0}x = x[/mathjaxinline]  Linear Approximations of basic functions near 0", "filename": "study-tab5-text1.html", "title": "Linear Approximations of basic functions near 0"}

{"pageid": 87, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@sequential+block@app_1-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@vertical+block@app_1-tab7", "text": "### Finding Local Maxima and Minima  Suppose the function [mathjaxinline]\\ f(x)[/mathjaxinline] is continuous at [mathjaxinline]x=a[/mathjaxinline] and has a critical point at [mathjaxinline]x=a[/mathjaxinline].  [mathjaxinline]\\ f[/mathjaxinline] has a local minimum at [mathjaxinline]x=a[/mathjaxinline] if [mathjaxinline]\\ f'(x) < 0[/mathjaxinline] just to the left of [mathjaxinline]a[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\ f'(x) > 0[/mathjaxinline] just to the right of [mathjaxinline]a[/mathjaxinline]. | ![See text on the left.](/static/images/u4app1_test2.svg)   ---|---   [mathjaxinline]\\ f[/mathjaxinline] has a local maximum at [mathjaxinline]x=a[/mathjaxinline] if [mathjaxinline]\\ f'(x) > 0[/mathjaxinline] just to the left of [mathjaxinline]a[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\ f'(x) < 0[/mathjaxinline] just to the right of [mathjaxinline]a[/mathjaxinline]. | ![See text on the left.](/static/images/u4app1_test1.svg)   The point [mathjaxinline]x=a[/mathjaxinline] is neither a local minimum nor a local maximum of [mathjaxinline]\\ f[/mathjaxinline] if [mathjaxinline]\\ f'(x)[/mathjaxinline] has the same sign just to the left of [mathjaxinline]a[/mathjaxinline] and just to the right of [mathjaxinline]a[/mathjaxinline]. | ![See text on the left.](/static/images/u4app1_test3.svg)      ###  Just to the left or right  When we use the phrase \u201c[mathjaxinline]\\ f'(x)>0[/mathjaxinline] just to the left of [mathjaxinline]a[/mathjaxinline],\" we mean that there is some open interval [mathjaxinline](a-c,a)[/mathjaxinline] of positive width [mathjaxinline]c[/mathjaxinline] on which [mathjaxinline]\\ f'[/mathjaxinline] is positive. This interval does not have to be very big, as long as it has some size!  Similarly, \u201c[mathjaxinline]\\ f'(x)>0[/mathjaxinline] just to the right of [mathjaxinline]a[/mathjaxinline]\" means that there is some open interval [mathjaxinline](a, a+d)[/mathjaxinline] of positive width [mathjaxinline]d[/mathjaxinline] on which [mathjaxinline]\\ f'[/mathjaxinline] is positive.  [Show](javascript: {return false;})  The First Derivative Test", "filename": "app_1-tab7-text1.html", "title": "The First Derivative Test"}

{"pageid": 88, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@sequential+block@app_1-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@vertical+block@app_1-tab17", "text": "[PDF Version](/static/pdf/graphing-summary.pdf)   **Definition of Critical Points**  The critical points of a function [mathjaxinline]\\ f(x)[/mathjaxinline] to be all points [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline] in the domain of [mathjaxinline]f(x)[/mathjaxinline] such that    * [mathjaxinline]f'(x) = 0[/mathjaxinline], or     * [mathjaxinline]f'(x)[/mathjaxinline] does not exist.   **The First Derivative Test**   **Finding Local Maxima and Minima**  Suppose the function [mathjaxinline]\\ f(x)[/mathjaxinline] is continuous at [mathjaxinline]x=a[/mathjaxinline] and has a critical point at [mathjaxinline]x=a[/mathjaxinline].  [mathjaxinline]\\ f[/mathjaxinline] has a local minimum at [mathjaxinline]x=a[/mathjaxinline] if [mathjaxinline]\\ f'(x) < 0[/mathjaxinline] just to the left of [mathjaxinline]a[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\ f'(x) > 0[/mathjaxinline] just to the right of [mathjaxinline]a[/mathjaxinline]. | ![See text on the left.](/static/images/u4app1_test2.svg)   ---|---   [mathjaxinline]\\ f[/mathjaxinline] has a local maximum at [mathjaxinline]x=a[/mathjaxinline] if [mathjaxinline]\\ f'(x) > 0[/mathjaxinline] just to the left of [mathjaxinline]a[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\ f'(x) < 0[/mathjaxinline] just to the right of [mathjaxinline]a[/mathjaxinline]. | ![See text on the left](/static/images/u4app1_test1.svg)   The point [mathjaxinline]x=a[/mathjaxinline] is neither a local minimum nor a local maximum of [mathjaxinline]\\ f[/mathjaxinline] if [mathjaxinline]\\ f'(x)[/mathjaxinline] has the same sign just to the left of [mathjaxinline]a[/mathjaxinline] and just to the right of [mathjaxinline]a[/mathjaxinline]. | ![See text on the left.](/static/images/u4app1_test3.svg)      ###  Just to the left or right  When we use the phrase \u201c[mathjaxinline]\\ f'(x)>0[/mathjaxinline] just to the left of [mathjaxinline]a[/mathjaxinline],\" we mean that there is some open interval [mathjaxinline](a-c,a)[/mathjaxinline] of positive width [mathjaxinline]c[/mathjaxinline] on which [mathjaxinline]\\ f'[/mathjaxinline] is positive. This interval does not have to be very big, as long as it has some size!  Similarly, \u201c[mathjaxinline]\\ f'(x)>0[/mathjaxinline] just to the right of [mathjaxinline]a[/mathjaxinline]\" means that there is some open interval [mathjaxinline](a, a+d)[/mathjaxinline] of positive width [mathjaxinline]d[/mathjaxinline] on which [mathjaxinline]\\ f'[/mathjaxinline] is positive.  [Show](javascript: {return false;})   **The Second Derivative Test**  Suppose that [mathjaxinline]x=a[/mathjaxinline] is a critical point of [mathjaxinline]\\ f[/mathjaxinline], with [mathjaxinline]\\ f'(a) = 0[/mathjaxinline].  If [mathjaxinline]\\ f^{\\prime \\prime }(a) > 0[/mathjaxinline], then [mathjaxinline]\\ f[/mathjaxinline] has a local minimum at [mathjaxinline]x=a[/mathjaxinline]. | ![See text on the left.](/static/images/u4app1_test4.svg)   ---|---   If [mathjaxinline]\\ f^{\\prime \\prime }(a) < 0[/mathjaxinline], then [mathjaxinline]\\ f[/mathjaxinline] has a local maximum at [mathjaxinline]x=a[/mathjaxinline]. | ![See text on the left.](/static/images/u4app1_test5.svg)   If [mathjaxinline]\\ f^{\\prime \\prime }(a) = 0[/mathjaxinline], or does not exist, then the test is inconclusive \u2014 there might be a local maximum, or a local minimum, or neither. |      **The First Derivative Test vs. the Second Derivative Test**  We've developed two tests for determining whether critical points are local minima or maxima. Each has its pros and cons.    * The Second Derivative Test requires just one value of [mathjaxinline]\\ f^{\\prime \\prime }[/mathjaxinline], but it is sometimes inconclusive.     * The First Derivative Test requires a bit more data, but is often able to provide more information as a result.   It is important to be comfortable using both tests!  **Definition of Inflection Point**  An **inflection point** is a point where the concavity of the function changes. That is the second derivative [mathjaxinline]f^{\\prime \\prime }(x)[/mathjaxinline] changes sign\u2014 [mathjaxinline]f^{\\prime \\prime }(x) > 0[/mathjaxinline] just to the left of [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]f^{\\prime \\prime }(x) < 0[/mathjaxinline] just to the right of [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline] (or vice versa).  Summary", "filename": "app_1-tab17-text1.html", "title": "Summary"}
