{"pageid": 95, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@sequential+block@study-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@vertical+block@study-tab3", "text": "**Properties of derivatives**  The derivative of a function is itself a function, and satisfies the following linearity properties.  **Derivatives of Constant Multiples**  If [mathjaxinline]g(x) = k\\ f(x)[/mathjaxinline] for some constant [mathjaxinline]k[/mathjaxinline], then  [mathjax]\\displaystyle g'(x) = k\\ f'(x)[/mathjax]|   ---|---      at all points where [mathjaxinline]\\ f[/mathjaxinline] is differentiable.  **Derivatives of Sums**  If [mathjaxinline]h(x) = f(x) + g(x)[/mathjaxinline], then  [mathjax]\\displaystyle h'(x) = f'(x) + g'(x)[/mathjax]|   ---|---      at all points where [mathjaxinline]\\ f[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]g[/mathjaxinline] are differentiable.  **Derivatives of Differences**  Similarly, if [mathjaxinline]j(x) = f(x) - g(x)[/mathjaxinline], then  [mathjax]\\displaystyle j'(x) = f'(x) - g'(x)[/mathjax]|   ---|---      at all points where [mathjaxinline]\\ f[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]g[/mathjaxinline] are differentiable.  Derivatives of Constant Multiples, Sums, and Differences", "filename": "study-tab3-text3.html", "title": "Derivatives of Constant Multiples, Sums, and Differences"}

{"pageid": 96, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@sequential+block@der_3-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@vertical+block@der_3-tab17", "text": "[PDF Version](/static/pdf/derivasfunct-summary.pdf)   **Recall secant and tangent lines**  In calculus, we often think of the function and its graph as being the same object. So to study functions, we often study their graphs.  In the last segment, we learned that the derivative at a point is the slope of the tangent line to the graph through that point. But when our graph is nice and smooth, without any discontinuities, corners, or other weird behavior, we can find the slope of the tangent line at any point. Thus we can think of the derivative of a function as a function.  **Example: The graph of a function and its derivative**  ![Plot of g of x from previous examples.](/static/images/u1der3_secondexample.svg)![Plot of g prime of x from previous examples.](/static/images/u1der3_2ndexamplederivativecomplete.svg)  Summary", "filename": "der_3-tab17-text1.html", "title": "Summary"}

{"pageid": 97, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@sequential+block@logistics-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@vertical+block@logistics-tab4", "text": "**Prerequisites**  This course has a global audience with students from a wide variety of backgrounds. To succeed in this course, you must have a solid foundation in    * algebra,     * geometry,     * trigonometry,     * exponents,     * logarithms, and     * limits   We know that many students may not have solid foundation in limits, so we have included an optional Unit 0 that introduces Limits. Understanding limits is essential to understand the first lecture on the definition of the derivative in Unit 1, some Homework problems on Continuity and Differentiability in Unit 1, and the first lecture on Limiting behavior and sketching functions in Unit 4.  Because we know you come from different backgrounds, we want to help you to choose the best path through this content. To aid us in this, please take the \u201cChoose your calculus adventure\" diagnostics. This will help you to determine if you have the skills to succeed, what skills you may need to review, and which units you may be able to skip!  Prerequisites", "filename": "logistics-tab4-text1.html", "title": "Prerequisites"}

{"pageid": 98, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@sequential+block@study-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@vertical+block@study-tab4", "text": "**The Chain Rule**  If [mathjaxinline]h(x) = f(g(x))[/mathjaxinline], then  [mathjax]h'(x) = f'\\left(g(x)\\right) g'(x)[/mathjax]|   ---|---      at all points where the derivatives [mathjaxinline]\\ f'(g(x))[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]g'(x)[/mathjaxinline] are defined.  Alternatively, if [mathjaxinline]y = f(u)[/mathjaxinline], and [mathjaxinline]u=g(x)[/mathjaxinline], then  [mathjax]\\left. \\frac{dy}{dx} \\right|_{x = a} = \\left. \\frac{dy}{du} \\right|_{u=g(a)} \\left. \\frac{du}{dx} \\right|_{x=a}[/mathjax]|   ---|---      at any point [mathjaxinline]x=a[/mathjaxinline] where the derivatives on the right hand side are defined.  The Chain Rule", "filename": "study-tab4-text4.html", "title": "The Chain Rule"}

{"pageid": 99, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@sequential+block@app_1-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@vertical+block@app_1-tab12", "text": "We've developed two tests for determining whether critical points are local minima or maxima. Each has its pros and cons.    * The Second Derivative Test requires just one value of [mathjaxinline]\\ f^{\\prime \\prime }[/mathjaxinline], but it is sometimes inconclusive.     * The First Derivative Test requires a bit more data, but is often able to provide more information as a result.   It is important to be comfortable using both tests!  First or Second?", "filename": "app_1-tab12-text1.html", "title": "First or Second?"}

{"pageid": 101, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@sequential+block@approx_3-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@vertical+block@approx_3-tab2", "text": "**Iterative numeric method** for finding **roots** of functions.  **Objectives**  At the end of this sequence, and after some practice, you should be able to:    * Apply **Newton's Method** to find roots of functions.     * Describe Newton's Method **geometrically**.     * Determine conditions **where Newton's Method will fail** to find a root.   **Contents: 10 pages**  5 videos (17 minutes at 1x speed) 10 questions  Objectives", "filename": "approx_3-tab2-text1.html", "title": "Objectives"}

{"pageid": 102, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@sequential+block@study-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@vertical+block@study-tab2", "text": "**Basic Continuous Functions**  Note: we have not proven all of the following facts, but you should feel free to use them.  The following functions are continuous at _all real numbers_ :    * all polynomials     * [mathjaxinline]\\sqrt[3]{x}[/mathjaxinline]     * [mathjaxinline]|x|[/mathjaxinline]     * [mathjaxinline]\\cos x[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\sin x[/mathjaxinline]     * exponential functions [mathjaxinline]a^x[/mathjaxinline] with base [mathjaxinline]a>0[/mathjaxinline]   The following functions are continuous _at the specified values_ of [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline]:    * [mathjaxinline]\\sqrt{x}[/mathjaxinline], for [mathjaxinline]x >0[/mathjaxinline]     * [mathjaxinline]\\tan x[/mathjaxinline], at all [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline] where it is defined     * logarithmic functions [mathjaxinline]\\log _{a} x[/mathjaxinline] with base [mathjaxinline]a>0[/mathjaxinline], for [mathjaxinline]x > 0[/mathjaxinline]   Basic Continuous Functions", "filename": "study-tab2-text5.html", "title": "Basic Continuous Functions"}

{"pageid": 103, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@sequential+block@study-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@vertical+block@study-tab3", "text": "**Second Derivative**  The second derivative of a function [mathjaxinline]\\ f(x)[/mathjaxinline] is the first derivative of [mathjaxinline]\\ f'(x)[/mathjaxinline], and is denoted by [mathjaxinline]f^{\\prime \\prime }(x)[/mathjaxinline] or [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{d^2f}{dx^2}[/mathjaxinline].  Second Derivative", "filename": "study-tab3-text6.html", "title": "Second Derivative"}

{"pageid": 104, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@sequential+block@approx_2-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@vertical+block@approx_2-tab2", "text": "**Quadratic approximations.**    **Degree 2 polynomial approximation.**    **Error**.  **Objectives**  At the end of this sequence, and after some practice, you should be able to:    * Understand why a **quadratic approximation** is the best fit **parabola** to a function near a given point.     * **Approximate functions** near a given point from the value of the first and second derivatives at that point.     * Use **big \u201cO\" notation** to describe order of magnitude of the error functions of linear and quadratic approximations..   **Contents: 14 pages**  7 videos (41 minutes at 1x speed) 19 questions  Objectives", "filename": "approx_2-tab2-text1.html", "title": "Objectives"}

{"pageid": 105, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@sequential+block@diff_6-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@vertical+block@diff_6-tab11", "text": "[mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle {\\arcsin x} =\\theta[/mathjaxinline] |  in [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\left[-\\pi /2,\\pi /2\\right][/mathjaxinline]| such that [mathjaxinline]\\sin \\theta = x.[/mathjaxinline]   ---|---|---   [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle {\\arccos x} =\\theta[/mathjaxinline] |  in [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\left[0,\\pi \\right][/mathjaxinline]|  such that [mathjaxinline]\\cos \\theta = x.[/mathjaxinline]   [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle {\\arctan x} =\\theta[/mathjaxinline] |  in [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\left(-\\pi /2,\\pi /2 \\right)[/mathjaxinline] | such that [mathjaxinline]\\tan \\theta = x.[/mathjaxinline]  The Inverse Trig Functions", "filename": "diff_6-tab11-text1.html", "title": "The Inverse Trig Functions"}

{"pageid": 107, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@sequential+block@approx_1-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@vertical+block@approx_1-tab5", "text": "Recall that the linear approximation of a function [mathjaxinline]\\ f(x)[/mathjaxinline] for [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline] near [mathjaxinline]x=0[/mathjaxinline] is given by the formula [mathjaxinline]\\ f(x) \\approx f(0) + f'(0)x[/mathjaxinline]. Find linear approximations of all of the basic functions near [mathjaxinline]x=0[/mathjaxinline]. We are going to be using these formulas a lot! So you may even want to memorize them.  We call the linear approximation the **linearization** of a function.  Linear Approximations", "filename": "approx_1-tab5-text1.html", "title": "Linear Approximations"}

{"pageid": 108, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@sequential+block@diff_1-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@vertical+block@diff_1-tab10", "text": "[PDF Version](/static/pdf/linearapprox-summary.pdf)   **Linear approximation**  The linear approximation for a function [mathjaxinline]\\ f[/mathjaxinline] near a point [mathjaxinline]x=a[/mathjaxinline] is given by the following equivalent formulas:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\Delta f[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\approx \\left. \\frac{df}{dx} \\right|_{x=a} \\cdot \\Delta x \\qquad \\ \\mathrm{for} \\ \\Delta x \\ \\mathrm{near} \\ 0[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle f(x)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\approx f'(a) (x-a) + f(a) \\ \\ \\ \\mathrm{for} \\ x \\ \\mathrm{near} \\ a[/mathjaxinline] |  |  Summary", "filename": "diff_1-tab10-text1.html", "title": "Summary"}

{"pageid": 109, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@sequential+block@study-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@vertical+block@study-tab3", "text": "**Definition of significant figures**  The number of _significant figures_ is the count of those digits that carry meaning with regards to precision.  **Examples**    * All non-zero digits are significant \u2013 1235 has 4 significant digits.     * Zeros appearing between nonzero digits are significant \u2013 101 has 3 significant digits.     * Trailing zeros in a number containing a decimal are significant \u2013 32.000 has 5 significant figures.   **Non Examples**    * Trailing zeros in a number with no decimal are _not_ significant \u2013 5400 has 2 significant figures.     * Leading zeros in a decimal number are not significant \u2013 0.0003 has 1 significant figure.     * Extraneous digits introduced in a computation to greater precision than measured data are _not_ significant \u2013 if .25 and .50 are measurements accurate to [mathjaxinline]\\pm[/mathjaxinline].01, then in the product (.25)(.50) = 0.125 the last 5 is _not_ significant.   Definition of significant figures", "filename": "study-tab3-text8.html", "title": "Definition of significant figures"}

{"pageid": 110, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@sequential+block@diff_3-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@vertical+block@diff_3-tab7", "text": "The numerator of the quotient rule looks like the product rule, except one of the terms is  subtracted from the other. This makes it important to remember which term comes first! The next few questions will help you develop an intuition about which term is subtracted and why.  Making Sense of the Quotient Rule", "filename": "diff_3-tab7-text1.html", "title": "Making Sense of the Quotient Rule"}

{"pageid": 111, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@sequential+block@diff_2-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@vertical+block@diff_2-tab2", "text": "**What functions can we differentiate so far?**  powers of [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline]   polynomials   sine and cosine    **Objectives**  At the end of this sequence, and after some practice, you should be able to:    * Differentiate **products** of functions.   **Contents: 12 pages**  6 videos (25 minutes 1x speed) 13 questions  What functions can we differentiate?", "filename": "diff_2-tab2-text1.html", "title": "What functions can we differentiate?"}

{"pageid": 112, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@sequential+block@study-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@vertical+block@study-tab3", "text": "**The Definition of the Derivative**  The **derivative** of a function [mathjaxinline]\\ f(x)[/mathjaxinline] at a point [mathjaxinline]x = a[/mathjaxinline] is defined to be  [mathjax]\\displaystyle f'(a) = \\lim _{b\\rightarrow a} \\frac{f(b) - f(a)}{b-a}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      **Geometrically**  Geometrically, the derivative [mathjaxinline]\\ f'(a)[/mathjaxinline] is the slope of the tangent line to the function [mathjaxinline]\\ f[/mathjaxinline] through the point [mathjaxinline](a, f(a))[/mathjaxinline].  The Definition of the Derivative", "filename": "study-tab3-text2.html", "title": "The Definition of the Derivative"}

{"pageid": 113, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@sequential+block@diff_6-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@vertical+block@diff_6-tab14", "text": "If [mathjaxinline]g[/mathjaxinline] is a (full or partial) inverse of a function [mathjaxinline]\\ f[/mathjaxinline], then  [mathjax]\\displaystyle {g'(x) = \\frac{1}{f'\\left(g(x)\\right)}}[/mathjax]|   ---|---      at all [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline] where [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle {f'\\left(g(x)\\right)}[/mathjaxinline] exists and is non-zero.  Derivatives of inverse functions", "filename": "diff_6-tab14-text1.html", "title": "Derivatives of inverse functions"}

{"pageid": 114, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@sequential+block@study-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@vertical+block@study-tab4", "text": "**Derivatives of the Inverse Trig Functions**  We now have more basic functions that we can differentiate.  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{d}{dx} \\arcsin x[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = \\frac{1}{\\sqrt{1-x^2}}[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{d}{dx} \\arccos x[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = -\\frac{1}{\\sqrt{1-x^2}}[/mathjaxinline] |  |   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{d}{dx} \\arctan x[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = \\frac{1}{1+x^2}[/mathjaxinline] |  |  Derivatives of Inverse Trig Functions", "filename": "study-tab4-text11.html", "title": "Derivatives of Inverse Trig Functions"}

{"pageid": 115, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@sequential+block@diff_5-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@vertical+block@diff_5-tab7", "text": "The implicit function that describes this curve is [mathjaxinline]x^4 -3x^2 + y^4 + y^2 + 2x^2 y^2 = 0[/mathjaxinline].  ![See text above.](/static/images/lemniscate.svg)  ###  Context for this curve  Suppose we have two point charges at [mathjaxinline](\\pm 1, 0)[/mathjaxinline]. The points where the potential energy of an electron would be equal to the potential energy at the origin is a curve called a lemniscate.  [Show](javascript: {return false;})  We can ask a lot of questions about this curve. For example:    1. What is the slope of the tangent line at the point [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\left(\\frac1{\\sqrt{2}},\\frac1{\\sqrt{2}}\\right)[/mathjaxinline]?, or     2. What are the points on this curve where the tangent line is horizontal?   Answering both of these questions requires finding [mathjaxinline]\\frac{dy}{dx}[/mathjaxinline]. Rather than solve for [mathjaxinline]y[/mathjaxinline], we'll use implicit differentiation. Here are questions to help you get started in answering these questions.  An Equipotential Curve", "filename": "diff_5-tab7-text1.html", "title": "An Equipotential Curve"}

{"pageid": 116, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@sequential+block@der_7-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@vertical+block@der_7-tab2", "text": "**What functions can we differentiate?**  polynomials   powers of [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline]  **Objectives**  At the end of this sequence, and after some practice, you should be able to:    * Differentiate **sine** and **cosine**.     * Use sine and cosine to model oscillations.   **Contents: 12 pages**  6 videos (27 minutes 1x speed) 11 questions  Objectives", "filename": "der_7-tab2-text1.html", "title": "Objectives"}

{"pageid": 117, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@sequential+block@hw1B-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@vertical+block@hw1B-tab2", "text": "**A bouncing ball**  The following function represents velocity of a bouncing ball.  ![The function is equal to 2 minus one half times t when t is between 0 and 6. When t equals 6, the function has a jump discontinuity. The function is then equal to negative t over 2 plus 4 when t is between 6 and 8.](/static/images/ps1_derivfunc.png)   Approximate velocity [mathjaxinline]v(t)[/mathjaxinline] of a bouncing ball  The function", "filename": "hw1B-tab2-text2.html", "title": "The function"}

{"pageid": 118, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@sequential+block@study-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@vertical+block@study-tab2", "text": "**Definition of One-Sided Limit**  ![](/static/images/u0lim1_leftright.svg)  Suppose [mathjaxinline]\\ f(x)[/mathjaxinline] gets really close to [mathjaxinline]R[/mathjaxinline] for values of [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline] that get really close to (but are not equal to) [mathjaxinline]a[/mathjaxinline] from the right. Then we say [mathjaxinline]R[/mathjaxinline] is the **right-hand limit** of the function [mathjaxinline]\\ f(x)[/mathjaxinline] as [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline] approaches [mathjaxinline]a[/mathjaxinline] from the right.  We write  [mathjaxinline]f(x) \\rightarrow R[/mathjaxinline] as [mathjaxinline]x \\rightarrow a^+[/mathjaxinline]   ---   or   [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle {\\lim _{x\\rightarrow \\mathbf{a^+}} f(x) = R}[/mathjaxinline].      If [mathjaxinline]\\ f(x)[/mathjaxinline] gets really close to [mathjaxinline]L[/mathjaxinline] for values of [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline] that get really close to (but are not equal to) [mathjaxinline]a[/mathjaxinline] from the left, we say that [mathjaxinline]L[/mathjaxinline] is the **left-hand limit** of the function [mathjaxinline]\\ f(x)[/mathjaxinline] as [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline] approaches [mathjaxinline]a[/mathjaxinline] from the left.  We write  [mathjaxinline]f(x) \\rightarrow L[/mathjaxinline] as [mathjaxinline]x \\rightarrow a^-[/mathjaxinline]   ---   or   [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle {\\lim _{x\\rightarrow \\mathbf{a^-}} f(x) = L}.[/mathjaxinline]  Definition of One-Sided Limit", "filename": "study-tab2-text1.html", "title": "Definition of One-Sided Limit"}

{"pageid": 119, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@sequential+block@approx_1-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@vertical+block@approx_1-tab6", "text": "**Approximations (likely nonlinear) of compositions**  Suppose that [mathjaxinline]g(x)[/mathjaxinline] is a function such that [mathjaxinline]g(0) =0[/mathjaxinline]. To find an approximation of a function [mathjaxinline]f(g(x))[/mathjaxinline] near [mathjaxinline]x=0[/mathjaxinline], we can take a linear approximation for [mathjaxinline]f(u)[/mathjaxinline] and then substitute [mathjaxinline]g(x)[/mathjaxinline] in for [mathjaxinline]u[/mathjaxinline]. The resulting approximation is likely nonlinear, but it is still an approximation! **Warning:** this only works if [mathjaxinline]g(0) = 0[/mathjaxinline].  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle f(u) \\approx f(0) + f'(0)u \\qquad \\Longrightarrow \\qquad f\\left(g(x)\\right) \\approx f(g(0)) + f'(g(0))g(x)[/mathjaxinline] |  | (5.6)   ---|---|---|---  Approximations (likely nonlinear) of compositions", "filename": "approx_1-tab6-text1.html", "title": "Approximations (likely nonlinear) of compositions"}

{"pageid": 120, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@sequential+block@study-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@vertical+block@study-tab4", "text": "**Implicit Differentiation**  To implicitly differentiate a function [mathjaxinline]\\ f(x)g(y) = 1[/mathjaxinline] with respect to [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline]:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\frac{d}{dx} \\left( f(x)g(y)\\right.[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =\\left. 1 \\right)[/mathjaxinline] |  | (7.5)   ---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\frac{d}{dx} \\left( f(x)g(y) \\right)[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = \\frac{d}{dx} 1[/mathjaxinline] |  | (7.6)   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\frac{d}{dx} \\left( f(x)g(y) \\right)[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = 0 \\quad \\textrm{(derivatives of constant functions are 0)}[/mathjaxinline] |  | (7.7)   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle f'(x)g(y) + f(x) \\frac{d}{dx}g(y)[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = 0 \\quad \\textrm{(product rule)}[/mathjaxinline] |  | (7.8)   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle f'(x)g(y) + f(x)g'(y) \\frac{dy}{dx}[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = 0 \\quad \\textrm{(chain rule)}[/mathjaxinline] |  | (7.9)  Implicit Differentiation", "filename": "study-tab4-text5.html", "title": "Implicit Differentiation"}

{"pageid": 121, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@sequential+block@study-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@vertical+block@study-tab5", "text": "**Quadratic Approximation**  The **quadratic approximation** near [mathjaxinline]x=a[/mathjaxinline] is the **best fit parabola** to [mathjaxinline]\\ f[/mathjaxinline] at the point [mathjaxinline]x=a[/mathjaxinline].  The formula for the quadratic approximation of a function [mathjaxinline]\\ f[/mathjaxinline] near a point [mathjaxinline]x=a[/mathjaxinline] is  [mathjax]\\displaystyle f(x) \\approx f(a) + f'(a)(x-a) + \\frac{f^{\\prime \\prime }(a)}{2}(x-a)^2.[/mathjax]| (7.15)   ---|---      When [mathjaxinline]a=0[/mathjaxinline], this quadratic approximation becomes  [mathjax]\\displaystyle f(x) \\approx f(0) + f'(0)x + \\frac{f^{\\prime \\prime }(0)}{2}x^2.[/mathjax]| (7.16)   ---|---  Quadratic Approximation Near Any Point", "filename": "study-tab5-text3.html", "title": "Quadratic Approximation Near Any Point"}

{"pageid": 122, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@sequential+block@diff_7-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@vertical+block@diff_7-tab10", "text": "[PDF Version](/static/pdf/exponential-summary.pdf)   **Properties of exponents**  Let [mathjaxinline]a[/mathjaxinline] be a positive real number.    * [mathjaxinline]a^0=1[/mathjaxinline]     * [mathjaxinline]a^1=a[/mathjaxinline]     * [mathjaxinline]a^{m}a^{n} = a^{m+n}[/mathjaxinline]     * [mathjaxinline]\\left(a^m\\right)^{n} = a^{mn}[/mathjaxinline]     * [mathjaxinline]a^{m/n} = \\sqrt[n]{a^m}[/mathjaxinline]   **Properties of exponential functions**  The function [mathjaxinline]\\ f(x) = a^x[/mathjaxinline] has base [mathjaxinline]a[/mathjaxinline] for a positive real number [mathjaxinline]a[/mathjaxinline].    * The function [mathjaxinline]a^x[/mathjaxinline] is a continuous function.     * The domain of [mathjaxinline]a^x[/mathjaxinline] is all real numbers.     * The range of [mathjaxinline]a^x[/mathjaxinline] is all positive real numbers.   **The derivative of an exponential function**  The derivative of the exponential function is  [mathjax]\\frac{d}{dx}a^x = M(a) a^x,[/mathjax]| (4.42)   ---|---      where the mystery number [mathjaxinline]M(a)[/mathjaxinline] is the slope of the tangent line at zero:  [mathjax]\\displaystyle M(a) =\\left. \\frac{d}{dx}a^x\\right|_{x=0} = \\lim _{\\Delta x\\rightarrow 0} \\frac{a^{\\Delta x}-1}{\\Delta x}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      **Definition of [mathjaxinline]e[/mathjaxinline]**  The base [mathjaxinline]e[/mathjaxinline] is the unique real number so that [mathjaxinline]M(e) = \\displaystyle \\left.\\frac{d}{dx} e^x\\right|_{x=0} = 1[/mathjaxinline]. Then  [mathjax]\\displaystyle \\frac{d}{dx}e^x = e^x.[/mathjax]| (4.43)   ---|---  Summary", "filename": "diff_7-tab10-text1.html", "title": "Summary"}

{"pageid": 123, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@sequential+block@der_7-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@vertical+block@der_7-tab7", "text": "For an alternate proof that uses the value of the derivative of [mathjaxinline]\\sin (\\theta )[/mathjaxinline] at [mathjaxinline]\\theta = 0[/mathjaxinline], see the proof below.  ###  Alternate algebraic proof  We want to find the limit [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\left.\\frac{d}{d\\theta }\\cos \\theta \\right|_{\\theta =0} = \\lim _{\\theta \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{\\cos \\theta -1}{\\theta }[/mathjaxinline]. In the video, we actually compute the negative of this limit [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\lim _{\\theta \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{1-\\cos \\theta }{\\theta }[/mathjaxinline]. Let's see another way to compute this limit algebraically using the limit of [mathjaxinline]\\sin (\\theta )[/mathjaxinline] at [mathjaxinline]\\theta =0[/mathjaxinline] that we just found.  By algebraic manipulation, we can write this argument of this limit in the following way:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\frac{1- \\cos \\theta }{\\theta }[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{1- \\cos \\theta }{\\theta } \\cdot \\frac{1+ \\cos \\theta }{1+ \\cos \\theta }[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.1)   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{1-\\cos ^2 \\theta }{\\theta (1+ \\cos \\theta )}[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.2)   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{\\sin ^2 \\theta }{\\theta (1+ \\cos \\theta )}[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.3)   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{\\sin \\theta }{\\theta }\\frac{\\sin \\theta }{1+ \\cos \\theta }[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.4)      Now take the limit as [mathjaxinline]\\theta[/mathjaxinline] approaches [mathjaxinline]0[/mathjaxinline]:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\lim _{\\theta \\rightarrow 0} \\left(\\frac{\\sin \\theta }{\\theta }\\right)\\left(\\frac{\\sin \\theta }{1+ \\cos \\theta }\\right)[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle (1)\\left(\\frac{0}{2}\\right) = 0.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.5)   ---|---|---|---|---|---      Note that we computed [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\lim _{\\theta \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{\\sin \\theta }{\\theta } =1[/mathjaxinline] using a geometric argument. And now we use the fact that [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\lim _{\\theta \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{\\sin \\theta }{1+\\cos \\theta } = \\frac{0}{2} = 0[/mathjaxinline].  [Show](javascript: {return false;})  Alternate proof", "filename": "der_7-tab7-text1.html", "title": "Alternate proof"}

{"pageid": 124, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@sequential+block@study-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@vertical+block@study-tab3", "text": "**Derivative of sine and cosine**  The first and second derivatives of sine and cosine:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\frac{d}{dx} \\sin (x)[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = \\cos (x)[/mathjaxinline] |  | (7.1)   ---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\frac{d}{dx} \\cos (x)[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = -\\sin (x)[/mathjaxinline] |  | (7.2)   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\frac{d^2}{dx^2} \\sin (x)[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = -\\sin (x)[/mathjaxinline] |  | (7.3)   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\frac{d^2}{dx^2} \\cos (x)[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = -\\cos (x)[/mathjaxinline] |  | (7.4)  Derivative of sine and cosine", "filename": "study-tab3-text9.html", "title": "Derivative of sine and cosine"}

{"pageid": 125, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@sequential+block@app_3-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@vertical+block@app_3-tab5", "text": "If [mathjaxinline]\\ f[/mathjaxinline] is continuous on a closed interval [mathjaxinline][a,b][/mathjaxinline], then there are points at which [mathjaxinline]\\ f[/mathjaxinline] attains its maximum and its minimum on [mathjaxinline][a,b][/mathjaxinline].  It is important to note that this is only guaranteed if the interval is finite and closed. We will talk about infinite intervals and open intervals a little later.  The proof of this theorem is beyond the scope of this course, so we will not present it here.  The Extreme Value Theorem", "filename": "app_3-tab5-text1.html", "title": "The Extreme Value Theorem"}

{"pageid": 128, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@sequential+block@der_3-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@vertical+block@der_3-tab2", "text": "  * Instantaneous rate of change     * Slope of the tangent line at a point     * **A function**   **Objectives**  At the end of this video, and after some practice, you should be able to:    * Understand the difference between a **derivative at a point** and the **derivative as a function**.     * Correlate graph of [mathjaxinline]\\ f[/mathjaxinline] to intervals of positive and negative values of the derivative.     * Be able to **sketch the graph** of [mathjaxinline]\\ f'[/mathjaxinline] given the graph of [mathjaxinline]\\ f[/mathjaxinline].   **Contents: 16 pages**  4 videos (19 minutes 1x speed) 15 questions  Objectives", "filename": "der_3-tab2-text1.html", "title": "Objectives"}

{"pageid": 129, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@sequential+block@diff_5-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@vertical+block@diff_5-tab3", "text": "The equation [mathjaxinline]x^2 + y^2 = 25[/mathjaxinline] describes a circle of radius 5.  ![See text above.](/static/images/implicitcircle.svg)  This curve does not satisfy the vertical line test\u2013there are two [mathjaxinline]y[/mathjaxinline] values for almost every [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline] value. {"pageid": 130, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@sequential+block@hw3B-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@vertical+block@hw3B-tab4", "text": "In this problem set, we will explore the idea of _sensitivity of measurement_. {"pageid": 132, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@sequential+block@study-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@vertical+block@study-tab4", "text": "**Definition of Inverse Function**  If functions [mathjaxinline]\\ f[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]g[/mathjaxinline] satisfy [mathjaxinline]g\\left(f(x)\\right) = x[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\ f\\left(g(y)\\right) = y[/mathjaxinline], then we say [mathjaxinline]g[/mathjaxinline] is the inverse of [mathjaxinline]\\ f[/mathjaxinline], and denote it by [mathjaxinline]\\ f^{-1}[/mathjaxinline]. (Similarly, [mathjaxinline]\\ f = g^{-1}[/mathjaxinline].)  If a function [mathjaxinline]\\ f[/mathjaxinline] has an inverse function [mathjaxinline]\\ f^{-1}[/mathjaxinline], then [mathjaxinline]\\ f^{-1}(b)= a[/mathjaxinline] if and only if [mathjaxinline]\\ f(a) = b[/mathjaxinline].  Definition of Inverse Function", "filename": "study-tab4-text6.html", "title": "Definition of Inverse Function"}

{"pageid": 133, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@sequential+block@der_2-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@vertical+block@der_2-tab19", "text": "[PDF Version](/static/pdf/geom-summary.pdf)   **Secant lines**  The **secant line** of a function [mathjaxinline]\\ f(x)[/mathjaxinline] over the interval [mathjaxinline]a \\leq x \\leq b[/mathjaxinline], is the line that passes through the points [mathjaxinline](a, f(a))[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline](b, f(b)).[/mathjaxinline]    * The slope of the secant line is [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{f(b)-f(a)}{b-a}[/mathjaxinline], which is the average rate of change of the function [mathjaxinline]f(x)[/mathjaxinline] over the interval [mathjaxinline]a\\leq x \\leq b[/mathjaxinline].     * The equation for the secant line is [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle y = \\frac{f(b)-f(a)}{b-a}(x-a) + f(a).[/mathjaxinline]   **Tangent lines**  The **tangent line** to a function [mathjaxinline]\\ f(x)[/mathjaxinline] at the point [mathjaxinline]x=a[/mathjaxinline] is the line that passes through the point [mathjaxinline](a, f(a))[/mathjaxinline], and whose slope is the instantaneous rate of change of [mathjaxinline]\\ f(x)[/mathjaxinline] at the point [mathjaxinline]x=a[/mathjaxinline]. This slope is the slope of the line you get if you imagine zooming in on the function until it looks like a line.    * The slope of the tangent line is [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle f'(a)[/mathjaxinline].     * The equation for the tangent line is [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle y = f'(a)(x-a) + f(a).[/mathjaxinline]   **Properties of tangent lines**  If the derivative of [mathjaxinline]\\ f(x)[/mathjaxinline] exists at [mathjaxinline]x=a[/mathjaxinline], then the tangent line exists. The tangent line may exist if the derivative is undefined at [mathjaxinline]x=a[/mathjaxinline] though. (Example [mathjaxinline]\\ f(x) = \\sqrt[3]{x}[/mathjaxinline] has a vertical tangent line at [mathjaxinline]x=0[/mathjaxinline].)  **What a tangent line is, and is not**  When introduced to tangent lines of circles, many students learn that a tangent is \u201ca line that touches the curve in only one point.\" This is true if your curve is a circle, but for many other curves and functions, this is a **terrible** definition. See the examples below.  ![Sine curve whose amplitude increases at either side of a point at which a horizontal line just touches the local maximum](/static/images/u1der2_infiniteintersectiontanline.svg) ![Sine curve and a line with slope negative 1 passing through the origin.](/static/images/u1der2_sincrossline.svg)  Summary", "filename": "der_2-tab19-text1.html", "title": "Summary"}

Properties of exponential functions", "filename": "diff_7-tab3-text2.html", "title": "Properties of exponential functions"}

Combine into graph.       **l'H\u00f4pital's Rule**   **L'H\u00f4pital's Rule Version 1: Indeterminate form [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac00[/mathjaxinline]**  If  [mathjax]\\begin{array}{l} \\displaystyle f(x) \\rightarrow 0\\\\\\ \\displaystyle g(x) \\rightarrow 0 \\end{array} \\quad \\text{ as } x \\rightarrow a,[/mathjax]|   ---|---      and the functions [mathjaxinline]\\ f[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]g[/mathjaxinline] are differentiable near the point [mathjaxinline]x=a[/mathjaxinline], then limit  [mathjax]\\displaystyle \\lim _{x \\rightarrow a} \\frac{f(x)}{g(x)} = \\lim _{x \\rightarrow a} \\frac{f'(x)}{g'(x)}[/mathjax]| (6.63)   ---|---      provided that the right hand limit exists or is [mathjaxinline]\\pm \\infty[/mathjaxinline].  **L'H\u00f4pital's Rule Version 2: Indeterminate form [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{\\infty }{\\infty }[/mathjaxinline]**  If  [mathjax]\\begin{array}{l} \\displaystyle f(x) \\rightarrow \\pm \\infty \\\\\\ \\displaystyle g(x) \\rightarrow \\pm \\infty \\end{array} \\quad \\text{ as } x \\rightarrow a,[/mathjax]|   ---|---      and the functions [mathjaxinline]\\ f[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]g[/mathjaxinline] are differentiable near the point [mathjaxinline]x=a[/mathjaxinline], then limit  [mathjax]\\displaystyle \\lim _{x \\rightarrow a} \\frac{f(x)}{g(x)} = \\lim _{x \\rightarrow a} \\frac{f'(x)}{g'(x)}[/mathjax]| (6.64)   ---|---      provided that the right hand limit exists or is [mathjaxinline]\\pm \\infty[/mathjaxinline].  Note that    * We can replace [mathjaxinline]a[/mathjaxinline] with [mathjaxinline]a^+[/mathjaxinline] or [mathjaxinline]a^-[/mathjaxinline] and the results (versions 1 and 2) still hold.     * We can replace [mathjaxinline]a[/mathjaxinline] with [mathjaxinline]\\pm \\infty[/mathjaxinline], and the results (versions 1 and 2) still hold.       **Other indeterminate forms**  Other indeterminate forms [mathjaxinline]0\\cdot \\infty[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]\\infty - \\infty[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]0^0[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]1^{\\infty }[/mathjaxinline], and [mathjaxinline]\\infty ^{0}[/mathjaxinline] should be rearranged to be of the form [mathjaxinline]0/0[/mathjaxinline] or [mathjaxinline]\\infty /\\infty[/mathjaxinline] in order to apply l'H\u00f4pital's rule. {"pageid": 152, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@sequential+block@diff_6-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@vertical+block@diff_6-tab19", "text": "[PDF Version](/static/pdf/inverse-summary.pdf)   **Definition of inverse function**  If functions [mathjaxinline]\\ f[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]g[/mathjaxinline] satisfy [mathjaxinline]g\\left(f(x)\\right) = x[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\ f\\left(g(y)\\right) = y[/mathjaxinline], then we say [mathjaxinline]g[/mathjaxinline] is the inverse of [mathjaxinline]\\ f[/mathjaxinline], and denote it by [mathjaxinline]\\ f^{-1}[/mathjaxinline]. (Similarly, [mathjaxinline]\\ f = g^{-1}[/mathjaxinline].)  If a function [mathjaxinline]\\ f[/mathjaxinline] has an inverse function [mathjaxinline]\\ f^{-1}[/mathjaxinline], then [mathjaxinline]\\ f^{-1}(b)= a[/mathjaxinline] if and only if [mathjaxinline]\\ f(a) = b[/mathjaxinline].  **Definition of one-to-one**  A function [mathjaxinline]\\ f[/mathjaxinline] is **one-to-one** if [mathjaxinline]\\ f(a) \\ne f(b)[/mathjaxinline] whenever [mathjaxinline]a\\ne b[/mathjaxinline]. It is one-to-one if and only if its graph satisfies the horizontal line test (no horizontal line intersects its graph at more than one place).  **Domain and range, interval notation**  Recall that the **domain** of a function [mathjaxinline]\\ f[/mathjaxinline] is the set of allowable input values. For instance, the domain of the function [mathjaxinline]\\ f(x) = 1/x[/mathjaxinline] is the set of all non-zero real numbers.  The **range** of [mathjaxinline]\\ f[/mathjaxinline] is the set of all possible output values. For instance, the range of the function [mathjaxinline]g(x) = x^2[/mathjaxinline] is the set of all real numbers that are non-negative.  We often use interval notation to express sets of numbers like domains and ranges. A **closed interval** , denoted [mathjaxinline][a,b][/mathjaxinline], is the set of numbers [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline] such that [mathjaxinline]a \\le x \\le b[/mathjaxinline].  An **open interval** , denoted [mathjaxinline](a,b)[/mathjaxinline], is the set of numbers [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline] such that [mathjaxinline]a < x < b[/mathjaxinline].  One can have a half-open, half-closed interval. For instance, [mathjaxinline][-1, 3)[/mathjaxinline] is the set of numbers [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline] such that [mathjaxinline]-1 \\le x <3[/mathjaxinline]. One can also use [mathjaxinline]\\pm \\infty[/mathjaxinline] as endpoints: [mathjaxinline](-\\infty , 0)[/mathjaxinline] is the set of numbers [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline] such that [mathjaxinline]-\\infty <x < 0[/mathjaxinline] (the set of negative numbers, in other words).  This notation using round parentheses for open intervals is not universal; many mathematicians use reversed square brackets instead. For instance, they would denote the interval [mathjaxinline]3 < x < 7[/mathjaxinline] as [mathjaxinline]]3,7[[/mathjaxinline] rather than [mathjaxinline](3,7)[/mathjaxinline]. In this course, however, we will stick to round parentheses for open intervals.  **The inverse trig functions**  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle {\\arcsin x} =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\theta[/mathjaxinline] in [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\left[-\\pi /2,\\pi /2\\right][/mathjaxinline]|  such that [mathjaxinline]\\sin \\theta = x.[/mathjaxinline]   ---|---|---   [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle {\\arccos x} =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\theta[/mathjaxinline] in [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\left[0,\\pi \\right][/mathjaxinline]|  such that [mathjaxinline]\\cos \\theta = x.[/mathjaxinline]   [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle {\\arctan x} =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\theta[/mathjaxinline] in [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\left(-\\pi /2,\\pi /2 \\right)[/mathjaxinline] |  such that [mathjaxinline]\\tan \\theta = x.[/mathjaxinline]      **Derivatives of inverse functions**  If [mathjaxinline]g[/mathjaxinline] is a (full or partial) inverse of a function [mathjaxinline]\\ f[/mathjaxinline], then  [mathjax]\\displaystyle {g'(x) = \\frac{1}{f'\\left(g(x)\\right)}}[/mathjax]|   ---|---      at all [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline] where [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle {f'\\left(g(x)\\right)}[/mathjaxinline] exists and is non-zero.  **Derivatives of arctrig functions**  Where defined,  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\frac{d}{dx}\\arcsin (x)[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{1}{\\sqrt{1-x^2}}[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{d}{dx}\\arccos (x)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{-1}{\\sqrt{1-x^2}}[/mathjaxinline] |  |   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{d}{dx}\\arctan (x)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{1}{1+x^2}[/mathjaxinline] |  |  Summary", "filename": "diff_6-tab19-text1.html", "title": "Summary"}

{"pageid": 157, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@sequential+block@der_4-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@vertical+block@der_4-tab2", "text": "Slopes of tangent lines   Limits    **Formulas**  **Objectives**  At the end of this sequence, and after some practice, you should be able to:    * Find **formulas for the derivatives** of simple functions.     * Know when to apply the **power rule**.     * Apply **linearity** to differential linear combinations.   **Contents: 18 pages**  13 videos (43 minutes 1x speed) 18 questions  Objectives", "filename": "der_4-tab2-text1.html", "title": "Objectives"}

{"pageid": 158, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@sequential+block@lim_3-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@vertical+block@lim_3-tab4", "text": "Let's consider the general case of a limit [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle {\\lim _{x\\rightarrow a} \\frac{f(x)}{g(x)}}[/mathjaxinline] where both the numerator and denominator approach 0.  When [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline] is near [mathjaxinline]a[/mathjaxinline], both [mathjaxinline]\\ f(x)[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]g(x)[/mathjaxinline] are close to zero but \u2013 crucially \u2013 not necessarily equal to zero. {"pageid": 160, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@sequential+block@logistics-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@vertical+block@logistics-tab6", "text": "We would like to thank you for your interest in this course! We hope you will take the time to read through the following few points about the course. It will give you a general feel for what you should expect in terms of workload, the course structure, and most importantly, what we hope you will get out of it.  From the beginning, the creators of this course wanted to offer a MITx course through edX that is on par with the **_18.01 Calculus_** class offered on campus at MIT.  **This is a hard course. It is easy to get discouraged, but don't!**  As you will notice, there are many components and in order to successfully complete all parts, you have to:    * understand the relevant subtleties of the derivative and apply derivatives to solving many different kinds of problems you haven't seen before     * critically think about approaches to solve the problem     * have good time management skills     * pay close attention to deadlines   You have to put in many hours, especially if your math skills are rusty (think algebra, geometry, and trigonometry). The only pre-requisite for this course is pre-calculus, but as with anything else, prior experience will make it easier for you. We are sure that students with limited background who will complete the first assignment perfectly, but they will probably put in a lot of work, ask questions, and after some frustrating but rewarding hours, manage to get the right answers. It is our intent that over the entire course, students should be able to get the work done in at most 10 hours a week. If, on average, you are spending lots more than that, let us know.  **We encourage research and independent learning.**  This goes back to keeping this course on par with the MIT campus one. Independent research comes in many forms. But ultimately, it comes down to paying attention, repetition of the concepts, and practice practice practice! Your research can be done in many forms:    * test solutions in a computer algebra system (MATLAB, Mathematica, Maple, Sage, or whatever)     * take tutorials from other sources (Khan Academy)     * sketch out solutions on paper     * read sections of text books, or online sources (Paul's Online Math Notes)     * post to the forums (or any of our social media platforms)     * discuss with other people in a face-to-face setting   **The staff and community TA's are here to help you.**  We cannot stress this enough!    * We are here to offer suggestions to put you on the right path.     * We are here to clarify mathematical subtleties.     * We are here to fix bugs in the course content.     * We are here to have interesting discussions.     * We are NOT here to give away answers.   While we are happy to post an explanation a couple of times, it becomes tedious and counterproductive to post the same explanation many times. We expect students to search the forums for similar problems and read the instructions carefully.  **We are all here to learn math.**  Be it from the videos, the exercises, or each other, we distinguish this course from other calculus courses because of the focus on students critically thinking about derivatives and applying them in interesting contexts. We will stress practice as a very important part of learning. Start early and do little bits every day, the material starts to seep in. This type of learning is highly encouraged.  If you think you can't keep up this time:    * Do your best!     * Keep asking questions!     * Try to learn as much as you can at your own pace!     * Then if you try the next offering again, with the knowledge you gained this time, you will conquer this course with more ease.   We hope you will keep at it and we wish you continued success in this course!  Getting into the MIT mindset", "filename": "logistics-tab6-text1.html", "title": "Getting into the MIT mindset"}

{"pageid": 162, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@sequential+block@study-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@vertical+block@study-tab4", "text": "**Properties of exponents**  Let [mathjaxinline]a[/mathjaxinline] be a positive real number.    * [mathjaxinline]a^0=1[/mathjaxinline]     * [mathjaxinline]a^1=a[/mathjaxinline]     * [mathjaxinline]a^{m}a^{n} = a^{m+n}[/mathjaxinline]     * [mathjaxinline]\\left(a^m\\right)^{n} = a^{mn}[/mathjaxinline]     * [mathjaxinline]a^{m/n} = \\sqrt[n]{a^m}[/mathjaxinline]   Properties of exponents", "filename": "study-tab4-text12.html", "title": "Properties of exponents"}

{"pageid": 163, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@sequential+block@lim_1-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@vertical+block@lim_1-tab14", "text": "Suppose [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle {\\lim _{x\\rightarrow a} f(x) = L}, \\qquad \\displaystyle {\\lim _{x\\rightarrow a} g(x) = M}.[/mathjaxinline]  Then we get the following Limit Laws:  Limit Law for Addition: |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle {\\lim _{x\\rightarrow a} \\left[f(x)+g(x)\\right] }[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]=[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]L+M[/mathjaxinline]   ---|---|---|---   Limit Law for Subtraction: |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle {\\lim _{x\\rightarrow a} \\left[f(x)-g(x)\\right] }[/mathjaxinline]| [mathjaxinline]=[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]L-M[/mathjaxinline]   Limit Law for Multiplication: |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle {\\lim _{x\\rightarrow a} \\left[f(x)\\cdot g(x)\\right] }[/mathjaxinline]| [mathjaxinline]=[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]L\\cdot M.[/mathjaxinline]      We also have part of the Limit Law for Division:  Limit Law for Division, Part 1: |  If [mathjaxinline]M\\ne 0[/mathjaxinline], then [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle {\\lim _{x\\rightarrow a} \\frac{f(x)}{g(x)} } = \\frac{L}{M}.[/mathjaxinline]   ---|---      We will discuss what happens when [mathjaxinline]M=0[/mathjaxinline] in a later section!  ###  Justifying the Limit Law for Multiplication  If [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle {\\lim _{x\\rightarrow a} f(x) = L}[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle {\\lim _{x\\rightarrow a} g(x) = M},[/mathjaxinline] then we can write  [mathjaxinline]f(x)[/mathjaxinline]|  [mathjaxinline]=[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]L + \\varepsilon _1[/mathjaxinline]   ---|---|---   [mathjaxinline]g(x)[/mathjaxinline]|  [mathjaxinline]=[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]M + \\varepsilon _2[/mathjaxinline],      where [mathjaxinline]\\varepsilon _1, \\varepsilon _2 \\rightarrow 0[/mathjaxinline] as [mathjaxinline]x \\rightarrow a[/mathjaxinline]. Then  [mathjax]f(x)g(x) = LM + \\varepsilon _1 M + \\varepsilon _2 L + \\varepsilon _1 \\varepsilon _2.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      As [mathjaxinline]L[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]M[/mathjaxinline] are constants and [mathjaxinline]\\varepsilon _1, \\varepsilon _2[/mathjaxinline] tend to zero, all three error terms [mathjaxinline]\\varepsilon _1 M[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]\\varepsilon _2 L[/mathjaxinline], and [mathjaxinline]\\varepsilon _1 \\varepsilon _2[/mathjaxinline] will go to zero as [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline] approaches [mathjaxinline]a[/mathjaxinline]. Hence  [mathjax]\\displaystyle {\\lim _{x\\rightarrow a} \\left[f(x)\\cdot g(x)\\right] } = L\\cdot M.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      [Show](javascript: {return false;})  Limit Laws", "filename": "lim_1-tab14-text1.html", "title": "Limit Laws"}

{"pageid": 164, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@sequential+block@der_1-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@vertical+block@der_1-tab14", "text": "[PDF Version](/static/pdf/derivdefn-summary.pdf)   **The Definition of the average rate of change**  The **average rate of change** of a function [mathjaxinline]\\ f(x)[/mathjaxinline] over an interval [mathjaxinline]a \\leq x \\leq b[/mathjaxinline] is defined to be  [mathjax]\\displaystyle \\frac{f(b) - f(a)}{b-a}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      **Definition of the derivative**  The **derivative** of a function [mathjaxinline]\\ f(x)[/mathjaxinline] at a point [mathjaxinline]x = a[/mathjaxinline] is defined to be  [mathjax]\\displaystyle f'(a) = \\lim _{b\\rightarrow a} \\frac{f(b) - f(a)}{b-a}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---  Summary", "filename": "der_1-tab14-text1.html", "title": "Summary"}

{"pageid": 165, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@sequential+block@forum-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@vertical+block@forum-tab1", "text": "The discussion forum is the tool for connecting with the community of online learners in this course. {"pageid": 168, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@sequential+block@der_1-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@vertical+block@der_1-tab2", "text": "  * **Instantaneous rate of change**   **Objectives**    * Describe what is meant by an **average rate of change** , and compute them with appropriate **units**.     * Describe the difference and relationship between the average rate of change and an **instantaneous rate of change**.     * Use a **limit** to find the instantaneous rate of change, also known as the **derivative** at a point.     * Interpret the **sign of a derivative** \\- positive, negative, or zero - as having real-world meaning.   **Contents: 13 pages**  6 videos (23 minutes 1x speed) 17 questions  Objectives", "filename": "der_1-tab2-text1.html", "title": "Objectives"}

{"pageid": 170, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@sequential+block@study-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@vertical+block@study-tab3", "text": "**The Definition of Average Rate of Change**  The **average rate of change** of a function [mathjaxinline]\\ f(x)[/mathjaxinline] over an interval [mathjaxinline]a \\leq x \\leq b[/mathjaxinline] is defined to be  [mathjax]\\displaystyle \\frac{f(b) - f(a)}{b-a}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      **Geometrically**  Geometrically, the average rate of change is the slope of the secant line through the points [mathjaxinline](a, f(a))[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline](b, f(b))[/mathjaxinline].  The Definition of Average Rate of Change", "filename": "study-tab3-text1.html", "title": "The Definition of Average Rate of Change"}

{"pageid": 171, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@sequential+block@approx_2-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@vertical+block@approx_2-tab10", "text": "A function [mathjaxinline]\\ f(x)[/mathjaxinline] is on the order [mathjaxinline]x^n[/mathjaxinline] near [mathjaxinline]x=0[/mathjaxinline], which is denoted using big \u201cO\" notation as [mathjaxinline]\\ f(x) = O(x^n)[/mathjaxinline] near [mathjaxinline]x=0[/mathjaxinline], if [mathjaxinline]\\left|f(x)\\right| \\leq k x^n[/mathjaxinline]. {"pageid": 172, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@sequential+block@hw4B-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@vertical+block@hw4B-tab3", "text": "Explain how your formula in Related Rates matched with the formula from Angles and Actors.  ###  See explanation  In the first part, [mathjaxinline]u=1[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]v=-1[/mathjaxinline], and [mathjaxinline]x=y=10[/mathjaxinline]. Plugging these numbers into the equation we found, we get the answer from above. {"pageid": 173, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@sequential+block@hw1B-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@vertical+block@hw1B-tab1", "text": "How does your car's speedometer work to determine how fast you are going?  Modern electric speedometers work because magnets placed on the axle rotate under a sensor that picks up the pulses of a magnetic field each time the wheel rotates. The speedometer then uses the time between pulses, and the travel distance of one rotation of the tires, to calculate the speed.  Food for thought: is the speedometer in a car computing an average or an instantaneous rate of change?  ###  See what we think  This is actually an average rate of change, since it is taking a change in distance from one tire rotation divided by a change in time between one pulse of the magnetic field and the next.  The two times are so close together, though, that this is a very good approximation for the instantaneous speed, which is the limit of the quotient as the two measurement times get closer and closer to one another. So in practice, it is OK to think of the speedometer reading as an instantaneous rate of change.  [Show](javascript: {return false;})  Speedometer", "filename": "hw1B-tab1-text1.html", "title": "Speedometer"}

{"pageid": 174, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@sequential+block@lim_1-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@vertical+block@lim_1-tab7", "text": "There are many possible limit behaviors.    * The right-hand and left-hand limits may both exist and be equal.     * The right-hand and left-hand limits may both exist, but may fail to be equal.     * A right- and/or left-hand limit could fail to exist due to blowing up to [mathjaxinline]\\pm \\infty[/mathjaxinline]. (Example: Consider the function [mathjaxinline]1/x[/mathjaxinline] near [mathjaxinline]x=0[/mathjaxinline].) In this case, we either say the limit blows up to infinity. We also say that the limit does not exist because [mathjaxinline]\\infty[/mathjaxinline] is not a real number!     * A right- and/or left-hand limit could fail to exist because it oscillates between many values and never settles down. In this case we say the limit does not exist.   Possible limit behaviors", "filename": "lim_1-tab7-text1.html", "title": "Possible limit behaviors"}

{"pageid": 176, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@sequential+block@lim_1-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@vertical+block@lim_1-tab2", "text": "**Objectives**  At the end of this sequence, and after some practice, you should be able to:    * Use a calculator to determine right and left hand limits.     * Identify right and left hand limits based on graphs.     * Determine if a limit exists based on values of right and left hand limits.     * Understand that the limit does not depend on the value of a function at the point of interest.   **Contents: 14 pages**  6 videos (24 minutes 1x speed) 17 questions  Objectives", "filename": "lim_1-tab2-text1.html", "title": "Objectives"}

{"pageid": 178, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@sequential+block@study-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@vertical+block@study-tab3", "text": "**Second Derivative and Concavity Summary**  On intervals where [mathjaxinline]\\ f^{\\prime \\prime } > 0[/mathjaxinline], the function [mathjaxinline]\\ f[/mathjaxinline] is concave up.  ![](/static/images/u1der5_concaveupgraph.svg)  On intervals where [mathjaxinline]\\ f^{\\prime \\prime } < 0[/mathjaxinline], the function [mathjaxinline]\\ f[/mathjaxinline] is concave down.  ![](/static/images/u1der5_concavedowngraph.svg)  Second Derivative and Concavity Summary", "filename": "study-tab3-text7.html", "title": "Second Derivative and Concavity Summary"}

{"pageid": 179, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@sequential+block@diff_6-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@vertical+block@diff_6-tab2", "text": "**What functions can we differentiate so far?**  powers of [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline]   polynomials   trigonometric functions   products of basic functions   quotients of basic functions   compositions of basic functions   implicit functions     **Objectives**  At the end of this sequence, and after some practice, you should be able to:    * Compute and evaluate inverse functions.     * Find graphs of inverse functions by reflecting the function graph across the diagonal.     * Find the derivative of **inverse** function.   **Contents: 19 pages**  9 videos (38 minutes 1x speed) 21 questions  What functions can we differentiate?", "filename": "diff_6-tab2-text1.html", "title": "What functions can we differentiate?"}

{"pageid": 180, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@sequential+block@diff_1-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@vertical+block@diff_1-tab6", "text": "The linear approximation for a function [mathjaxinline]\\ f[/mathjaxinline] near a point [mathjaxinline]x=a[/mathjaxinline] is given by the following equivalent formulas:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\Delta f[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\approx \\left. \\frac{df}{dx} \\right|_{x=a} \\cdot \\Delta x \\qquad \\ \\mathrm{for} \\ \\Delta x \\ \\mathrm{near} \\ 0[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle f(x)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\approx f'(a) (x-a) + f(a) \\ \\ \\ \\mathrm{for} \\ x \\ \\mathrm{near} \\ a[/mathjaxinline] |  |  Equivalent Formulas for Linear Approximations", "filename": "diff_1-tab6-text1.html", "title": "Equivalent Formulas for Linear Approximations"}

{"pageid": 181, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@sequential+block@diff_6-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@vertical+block@diff_6-tab7", "text": "**No inverse?**  You may have noticed that we've been constantly saying, \u201c **If** [mathjaxinline]\\ f[/mathjaxinline] has an inverse...\" These next few questions explain what could go wrong. {"pageid": 182, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@sequential+block@study-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@vertical+block@study-tab4", "text": "**The derivative of an exponential function**  The derivative of the exponential function is  [mathjax]\\frac{d}{dx}a^x = M(a) a^x,[/mathjax]| (7.10)   ---|---      where the mystery number [mathjaxinline]M(a)[/mathjaxinline] is the slope of the tangent line at zero:  [mathjax]\\displaystyle M(a) =\\left. \\frac{d}{dx}a^x\\right|_{x=0} = \\lim _{\\Delta x\\rightarrow 0} \\frac{a^{\\Delta x}-1}{\\Delta x}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---  The derivative of an exponential", "filename": "study-tab4-text14.html", "title": "The derivative of an exponential"}

{"pageid": 183, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@sequential+block@study-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@vertical+block@study-tab4", "text": "**Properties of exponential functions**  The function [mathjaxinline]\\ f(x) = a^x[/mathjaxinline] has base [mathjaxinline]a[/mathjaxinline] for a positive real number [mathjaxinline]a[/mathjaxinline].    * The function [mathjaxinline]a^x[/mathjaxinline] is a continuous function.     * The domain of [mathjaxinline]a^x[/mathjaxinline] is all real numbers.     * The range of [mathjaxinline]a^x[/mathjaxinline] is all positive real numbers.   Properties of exponential functions", "filename": "study-tab4-text13.html", "title": "Properties of exponential functions"}

{"pageid": 184, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@sequential+block@der_4-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@vertical+block@der_4-tab11", "text": "We've seen that differentiation \u201crespects\" addition and multiplication by a constant. That is, if you take a derivative of a sum of functions, you get the same thing as if you differentiated each part, and then added the derivatives. Similarly, if you take the derivative of [mathjaxinline]k[/mathjaxinline] times a function, where [mathjaxinline]k[/mathjaxinline] is a constant, then you get [mathjaxinline]k[/mathjaxinline] times the derivative of the original function.  Respecting addition and constant multiplication in this way is called \u201clinearity,\" and it is an important property of the derivative operation! We combine both parts of linearity in the following problems.  What is linearity?", "filename": "der_4-tab11-text1.html", "title": "What is linearity?"}

{"pageid": 185, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@sequential+block@lim_2-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@vertical+block@lim_2-tab6", "text": "A function [mathjaxinline]\\ f(x)[/mathjaxinline] is **continuous** if for every point [mathjaxinline]c[/mathjaxinline] in the domain of [mathjaxinline]\\ f(x)[/mathjaxinline], the function [mathjaxinline]\\ f[/mathjaxinline] is continuous at the point [mathjaxinline]x=c[/mathjaxinline].  Definition of continuous functions", "filename": "lim_2-tab6-text1.html", "title": "Definition of continuous functions"}

{"pageid": 187, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@sequential+block@study-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@vertical+block@study-tab3", "text": "**Properties of Leibniz notation**    *  **Units:** If [mathjaxinline]P[/mathjaxinline] has units of pressure, and [mathjaxinline]t[/mathjaxinline] has units of [mathjaxinline]time[/mathjaxinline], then [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{dP}{dt}[/mathjaxinline] has units of pressure per time.     * **Evaluating at points:** If we want to take the derivative at a particular point [mathjaxinline]x = 3[/mathjaxinline], then we use the notation [mathjaxinline]\\left.\\displaystyle \\frac{df}{dx}\\right|_{x=3}[/mathjaxinline]. The bar is read as \u201cevaluated at\".     * **Derivatives act on functions:**      * We can write [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{d(x^2)}{dx}[/mathjaxinline] for the derivative of [mathjaxinline]x^2[/mathjaxinline].       * If a formula is long, we can write [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{d}{dy} \\left(y^3 + 2y^2 \\right).[/mathjaxinline]   Properties of Leibniz notation", "filename": "study-tab3-text5.html", "title": "Properties of Leibniz notation"}

{"pageid": 189, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@sequential+block@study-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@vertical+block@study-tab6", "text": "**The First Derivative Test**   **Finding Local Maxima and Minima**  Suppose the function [mathjaxinline]\\ f(x)[/mathjaxinline] is continuous at [mathjaxinline]x=a[/mathjaxinline] and has a critical point at [mathjaxinline]x=a[/mathjaxinline].  [mathjaxinline]\\ f[/mathjaxinline] has a local minimum at [mathjaxinline]x=a[/mathjaxinline] if [mathjaxinline]\\ f'(x) < 0[/mathjaxinline] just to the left of [mathjaxinline]a[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\ f'(x) > 0[/mathjaxinline] just to the right of [mathjaxinline]a[/mathjaxinline]. | ![](/static/images/u4app1_test2.svg)   ---|---   [mathjaxinline]\\ f[/mathjaxinline] has a local maximum at [mathjaxinline]x=a[/mathjaxinline] if [mathjaxinline]\\ f'(x) > 0[/mathjaxinline] just to the left of [mathjaxinline]a[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\ f'(x) < 0[/mathjaxinline] just to the right of [mathjaxinline]a[/mathjaxinline]. | ![](/static/images/u4app1_test1.svg)   The point [mathjaxinline]x=a[/mathjaxinline] is neither a local minimum nor a local maximum of [mathjaxinline]\\ f[/mathjaxinline] if [mathjaxinline]\\ f'(x)[/mathjaxinline] has the same sign just to the left of [mathjaxinline]a[/mathjaxinline] and just to the right of [mathjaxinline]a[/mathjaxinline]. | ![](/static/images/u4app1_test3.svg)      ###  Just to the left or right  When we use the phrase \u201c[mathjaxinline]\\ f'(x)>0[/mathjaxinline] just to the left of [mathjaxinline]a[/mathjaxinline],\" we mean that there is some open interval [mathjaxinline](a-c,a)[/mathjaxinline] of positive width [mathjaxinline]c[/mathjaxinline] on which [mathjaxinline]\\ f'[/mathjaxinline] is positive. This interval does not have to be very big, as long as it has some size!  Similarly, \u201c[mathjaxinline]\\ f'(x)>0[/mathjaxinline] just to the right of [mathjaxinline]a[/mathjaxinline]\" means that there is some open interval [mathjaxinline](a, a+d)[/mathjaxinline] of positive width [mathjaxinline]d[/mathjaxinline] on which [mathjaxinline]\\ f'[/mathjaxinline] is positive.  [Show](javascript: {return false;})  The First Derivative Test", "filename": "study-tab6-text2.html", "title": "The First Derivative Test"}

{"pageid": 190, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@sequential+block@diff_8-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@vertical+block@diff_8-tab14", "text": "[PDF Version](/static/pdf/logarithm-summary.pdf)   **Properties of [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline]**  [mathjaxinline]\\log _{10}(x)[/mathjaxinline] is the inverse function of [mathjaxinline]10^x[/mathjaxinline].  The natural log, denoted [mathjaxinline]\\ln (x)[/mathjaxinline], is the inverse function of [mathjaxinline]e^x[/mathjaxinline].    * [mathjaxinline]\\ln e^x =x[/mathjaxinline]     * [mathjaxinline]e^{\\ln x} = x[/mathjaxinline]     * [mathjaxinline]\\ln (ab) = \\ln (a) + \\ln (b)[/mathjaxinline]     * [mathjaxinline]\\ln (a^b) = b\\ln (a)[/mathjaxinline]   **The derivative of the natural logarithm**  Our collection of basic functions that we can differentiate now has one more entry:  [mathjax]\\frac{d}{dx} \\ln x = \\frac{1}{x}[/mathjax]|   ---|---      **Differentiating exponential functions with other bases**  For any positive constant [mathjaxinline]a[/mathjaxinline],  [mathjax]\\frac{d}{dx} a^x = a^x \\ln a.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      **Differentiation methods**  ### Method 1: Change to base e  To calculate [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\left( f(x)^{g(x)} \\right)^{\\prime },[/mathjaxinline]    * first change base [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle f(x)^{g(x)} = e^{g(x)\\ln f(x)}[/mathjaxinline],     * then differentiate using the chain rule, and the derivatives of the exponential and natural logarithm functions.   ### Method 2: Logarithmic differentiation  To calculate [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle u^{\\prime },[/mathjaxinline]    * first calculate [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\left(\\ln (u)\\right)^{\\prime }[/mathjaxinline],     * then use the formula   [mathjax]\\displaystyle \\frac{u^{\\prime }}{u} = \\left(\\ln (u)\\right)^{\\prime }[/mathjax]|   ---|---      and solve for [mathjaxinline]u'[/mathjaxinline].  Summary", "filename": "diff_8-tab14-text1.html", "title": "Summary"}

{"pageid": 191, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@sequential+block@approx_1-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@vertical+block@approx_1-tab8", "text": "To find the linear approximation of a function [mathjaxinline]h(x) = f(x)g(x)[/mathjaxinline] near [mathjaxinline]x=0[/mathjaxinline], it suffices to find a linear approximation for [mathjaxinline]f(x)[/mathjaxinline], find a linear approximation for [mathjaxinline]g(x)[/mathjaxinline], and then the linear approximation for [mathjaxinline]h(x)[/mathjaxinline] is the product of these two approximations where we cancel all of the terms that are quadratic (or higher for more products).  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle h(x)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle f(x)g(x)[/mathjaxinline] |  | (5.7)   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle f(x)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\approx[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle f(0) + f'(0)x[/mathjaxinline] |  | (5.8)   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle g(x)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\approx[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle g(0) + g'(0)x[/mathjaxinline] |  | (5.9)   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle h(x)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\approx[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\left(f(0) + f'(0)x\\right)\\left(g(0) + g'(0)x\\right)[/mathjaxinline] |  | (5.10)   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle f(0)g(0) + \\left(f'(0)g(0) +f(0)g'(0)\\right)x + f'(0)g'(0)x^2[/mathjaxinline] |  | (5.11)   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\approx[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle f(0)g(0) + \\left(f'(0)g(0) +f(0)g'(0)\\right)x[/mathjaxinline] |  | (5.12)  Linear approximations of products", "filename": "approx_1-tab8-text1.html", "title": "Linear approximations of products"}

{"pageid": 192, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@sequential+block@diff_8-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@vertical+block@diff_8-tab2", "text": "**What functions can we differentiate so far?**  powers of [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline]   polynomials   trigonometric functions and their inverses   products of basic functions   quotients of basic functions   compositions of basic functions   implicit functions   inverses of basic functions   the exponential function  **Objectives**  At the end of this sequence, and after some practice, you should be able to:    * Differentiate the **logarithm function**.     * Identify the derivative of [mathjaxinline]a^x[/mathjaxinline] explicitly.     * Use the **inverse relationship** of [mathjaxinline]e[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\ln[/mathjaxinline] to differentiate complicated exponents.     * Use **logarithmic differentiation** to deal with functions whose exponents are varying.   **Contents: 14 pages**  8 videos (42 minutes 1x speed) 16 questions  What functions can we differentiate?", "filename": "diff_8-tab2-text1.html", "title": "What functions can we differentiate?"}

{"pageid": 194, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@sequential+block@hw3B-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@vertical+block@hw3B-tab4", "text": "**Food for thought**  There is some measurement error in determining [mathjaxinline]h[/mathjaxinline], in which case are you more confident in your position?
