{"pageid": 195, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@sequential+block@lim_2-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@vertical+block@lim_2-tab3", "text": "We say that a function [mathjaxinline]\\ f[/mathjaxinline] is **continuous at a point** [mathjaxinline]x = a[/mathjaxinline] if  [mathjax]\\displaystyle {\\lim _{x\\rightarrow a} f(x) } = f(a).[/mathjax]|   ---|---      In particular, if either [mathjaxinline]\\ f(a)[/mathjaxinline] or [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle {\\lim _{x\\rightarrow a} f(x) }[/mathjaxinline] fails to exist, then [mathjaxinline]\\ f[/mathjaxinline] is discontinuous at [mathjaxinline]a[/mathjaxinline].  We say that a function [mathjaxinline]\\ f[/mathjaxinline] is **right- continuous at a point** [mathjaxinline]x = a[/mathjaxinline] if [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle {\\lim _{x\\rightarrow a^+} f(x) } = f(a)[/mathjaxinline].  We say that a function [mathjaxinline]\\ f[/mathjaxinline] is **left-continuous at a point** [mathjaxinline]x = a[/mathjaxinline] if [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle {\\lim _{x\\rightarrow a^-} f(x) } = f(a)[/mathjaxinline].  It is sometimes useful to classify certain types of discontinuities.  If the left-hand limit [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle {\\lim _{x\\rightarrow a^-} f(x) }[/mathjaxinline] and the right-hand limit [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle {\\lim _{x\\rightarrow a^+} f(x) }[/mathjaxinline] both exist at a point [mathjaxinline]x=a[/mathjaxinline], but they are not equal, then we say that [mathjaxinline]\\ f[/mathjaxinline] has a **jump discontinuity** at [mathjaxinline]x=a[/mathjaxinline].  ![](/static/images/u0lim2_jump.svg)  If the overall limit [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle {\\lim _{x\\rightarrow a} f(x) }[/mathjaxinline] exists (i.e., the left- and right-hand limits agree), but the overall limit does not equal [mathjaxinline]\\ f(a)[/mathjaxinline], then we say that [mathjaxinline]\\ f[/mathjaxinline] has a **removable discontinuity** at [mathjaxinline]x=a[/mathjaxinline].  ![](/static/images/u0lim2_removable.svg)  Definition of continuous", "filename": "lim_2-tab3-text1.html", "title": "Definition of continuous"}

{"pageid": 196, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@sequential+block@diff_7-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@vertical+block@diff_7-tab5", "text": "The derivative of the exponential function is  [mathjax]\\frac{d}{dx}a^x = M(a) a^x,[/mathjax]| (4.34)   ---|---      where the mystery number [mathjaxinline]M(a)[/mathjaxinline] is the slope of the tangent line at zero:  [mathjax]\\displaystyle M(a) =\\left. \\frac{d}{dx}a^x\\right|_{x=0} = \\lim _{\\Delta x\\rightarrow 0} \\frac{a^{\\Delta x}-1}{\\Delta x}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---  The derivative of an exponential", "filename": "diff_7-tab5-text1.html", "title": "The derivative of an exponential"}

{"pageid": 197, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@sequential+block@approx_2-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@vertical+block@approx_2-tab5", "text": "The best fit quadratic to a function [mathjaxinline]\\ f(x)[/mathjaxinline] at the point [mathjaxinline]x=0[/mathjaxinline] is the quadratic function [mathjaxinline]q(x)[/mathjaxinline] whose value agrees with the value of [mathjaxinline]\\ f[/mathjaxinline] at [mathjaxinline]x=0[/mathjaxinline], and whose first and second derivatives agree with the first and second derivatives of [mathjaxinline]\\ f[/mathjaxinline] at [mathjaxinline]x=0[/mathjaxinline], i.e.:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle f(0)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = q(0)[/mathjaxinline] |  | (5.35)   ---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle f'(0)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = q'(0)[/mathjaxinline] |  | (5.36)   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle f^{\\prime \\prime }(0)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = q^{\\prime \\prime }(0)[/mathjaxinline] |  | (5.37)  Best fit quadratic", "filename": "approx_2-tab5-text1.html", "title": "Best fit quadratic"}

{"pageid": 198, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@sequential+block@der_5-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@vertical+block@der_5-tab6", "text": "  * **Units:** If [mathjaxinline]P[/mathjaxinline] has units of pressure, and [mathjaxinline]t[/mathjaxinline] has units of [mathjaxinline]time[/mathjaxinline], then [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{dP}{dt}[/mathjaxinline] has units of pressure per time.     * **Evaluating at points:** If we want to take the derivative at a particular point [mathjaxinline]x = 3[/mathjaxinline], then we use the notation [mathjaxinline]\\left.\\displaystyle \\frac{df}{dx}\\right|_{x=3}[/mathjaxinline]. {"pageid": 199, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@sequential+block@study-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@vertical+block@study-tab6", "text": "**The Extreme Value Theorem**  If [mathjaxinline]\\ f[/mathjaxinline] is continuous on a closed interval [mathjaxinline][a,b][/mathjaxinline], then there are points at which [mathjaxinline]\\ f[/mathjaxinline] attains its maximum and its minimum on [mathjaxinline][a,b][/mathjaxinline].  **Maxima and Minima**  The maxima and minima will be attained at either a critical point or an end point. {"pageid": 203, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@sequential+block@diff_8-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@vertical+block@diff_8-tab10", "text": "**Complete proof of the power rule for all real powers [mathjaxinline]x^r[/mathjaxinline]**  We can use both methods for differentiating exponential functions here to give a proof of the power rule for any power [mathjaxinline]r[/mathjaxinline], rational or irrational. Let's see how.  Note that you may want to try to work these proofs out on your own first as practice using the rules we learned above.  ###  Proof by Method 1  Method 1 is to change the base to [mathjaxinline]e[/mathjaxinline].  | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle x^r[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = \\left(e^{\\ln x}\\right)^r = e^{r\\ln x}[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.51)   ---|---|---|---|---   Apply the chain rule using [mathjaxinline]u = r\\ln x[/mathjaxinline].  | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\frac{d}{dx}e^u[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =\\quad \\frac{de^u}{du}\\frac{du}{dx}[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.52)   ---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = \\quad e^{r\\ln x} \\frac{r}{x}[/mathjaxinline] | | (4.53)   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =\\quad x^r\\frac{r}{x} = rx^{r-1}[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.54)   This is what we expected to find! And this proof holds for [mathjaxinline]r[/mathjaxinline] any number, rational or irrational.  [Show](javascript: {return false;})  ###  Proof by Method 2  Method 2 is to apply the natural logarithm and differentiate.  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\ln x^r[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = r\\ln x[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.55)   ---|---|---|---|---      The derivative is [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{r}{x}[/mathjaxinline]. Now we need to use the formula:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\frac{u^{\\prime }}{u}[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = \\quad \\left(\\ln u\\right)^{\\prime }[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.56)   ---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\frac{\\left( x^r \\right)^{\\prime }}{x^r}[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = \\quad \\frac{r}{x}[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.57)   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\left( x^r \\right)^{\\prime }[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = \\frac{rx^r}{x} = \\quad rx^{r-1}.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.58)      Thus we find [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{d}{dx} x^r = rx^{r-1}[/mathjaxinline], which is what we expected! And this proof holds for [mathjaxinline]r[/mathjaxinline] any number, rational or irrational.  [Show](javascript: {return false;})  Proof of the power rule for all real numbers", "filename": "diff_8-tab10-text2.html", "title": "Proof of the power rule for all real numbers"}

{"pageid": 206, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@sequential+block@diff_7-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@vertical+block@diff_7-tab2", "text": "**What functions can we differentiate so far?**  powers of [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline]   polynomials   trigonometric functions   products of basic functions   quotients of basic functions   compositions of basic functions   inverses of basic functions     **Objectives**  At the end of this sequence, and after some practice, you should be able to:    * Differentiate the **exponential** function.     * Define the number [mathjaxinline]e[/mathjaxinline] in terms of the value of the derivative [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\left.\\frac{d}{dx}e^x\\right|_{x=0}[/mathjaxinline].   **Contents: 9 pages**  5 videos (21 minutes 1x speed) 10 questions  What functions can we differentiate?", "filename": "diff_7-tab2-text1.html", "title": "What functions can we differentiate?"}

{"pageid": 207, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@sequential+block@der_6-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@vertical+block@der_6-tab17", "text": "[PDF Version](/static/pdf/higherderivs-summary.pdf)   **Second derivative**  The second derivative of a function [mathjaxinline]\\ f(x)[/mathjaxinline] is the first derivative of [mathjaxinline]\\ f'(x)[/mathjaxinline], and is denoted by [mathjaxinline]f^{\\prime \\prime }(x)[/mathjaxinline] or [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{d^2f}{dx^2}[/mathjaxinline].  **Higher derivatives**  The [mathjaxinline]n[/mathjaxinline]th derivative of a function [mathjaxinline]\\ f(x)[/mathjaxinline] is the first derivative of [mathjaxinline]\\ f^{(n-1)}(x)[/mathjaxinline], and is denoted by [mathjaxinline]f^{(n)}(x)[/mathjaxinline] or [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{d^nf}{dx^n}[/mathjaxinline].  **Second derivative and concavity summary**  On intervals where [mathjaxinline]\\ f^{\\prime \\prime } > 0[/mathjaxinline], the function [mathjaxinline]\\ f[/mathjaxinline] is concave up.  ![Function increases, then decreases, then increases. Highlighted portion starts at the inflection point where the function is decreasing and then increasing.](/static/images/u1der5_concaveupgraph.svg)  On intervals where [mathjaxinline]\\ f^{\\prime \\prime } < 0[/mathjaxinline], the function [mathjaxinline]\\ f[/mathjaxinline] is concave down.  ![Function increases, then decreases, then increases. Highlighted portion starts on the left where the function is increasing and then decreasing, ending at the inflection point.](/static/images/u1der5_concavedowngraph.svg)  Points where the graph of a function changes from concave up to concave down, or vice versa, are called **inflection points**.  **Position, velocity, acceleration**  If [mathjaxinline]x(t)[/mathjaxinline] is a function that describes position as a function of time, then:    * [mathjaxinline]x'(t)[/mathjaxinline] is the velocity, and     * [mathjaxinline]x^{\\prime \\prime }(t)[/mathjaxinline] is the acceleration.   Summary", "filename": "der_6-tab17-text1.html", "title": "Summary"}

We write  [mathjaxinline]f(x) \\rightarrow L[/mathjaxinline] as [mathjaxinline]x \\rightarrow a^-[/mathjaxinline]   ---   or   [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle {\\lim _{x\\rightarrow \\mathbf{a^-}} f(x) = L}.[/mathjaxinline]  Definitions of right-hand and left-hand limits", "filename": "lim_1-tab5-text1.html", "title": "Definitions of right-hand and left-hand limits"}

{"pageid": 209, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@sequential+block@diff_7-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@vertical+block@diff_7-tab3", "text": "Let [mathjaxinline]a[/mathjaxinline] be a positive real number.    * [mathjaxinline]a^0=1[/mathjaxinline]     * [mathjaxinline]a^1=a[/mathjaxinline]     * [mathjaxinline]a^{m}a^{n} = a^{m+n}[/mathjaxinline]     * [mathjaxinline]\\left(a^m\\right)^{n} = a^{mn}[/mathjaxinline]     * [mathjaxinline]a^{m/n} = \\sqrt[n]{a^m}[/mathjaxinline]   Properties of exponents", "filename": "diff_7-tab3-text1.html", "title": "Properties of exponents"}

{"pageid": 210, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@sequential+block@diff_8-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@vertical+block@diff_8-tab10", "text": "**Differentiation methods**  ### Method 1: Change to base e  To calculate [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\left( f(x)^{g(x)} \\right)^{\\prime },[/mathjaxinline]    * first change base [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle f(x)^{g(x)} = e^{g(x)\\ln f(x)}[/mathjaxinline],     * then differentiate using the chain rule, and the derivatives of the exponential and natural logarithm functions.   ### Method 2: Logarithmic differentiation  To calculate [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle u^{\\prime },[/mathjaxinline]    * first calculate [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\left(\\ln (u)\\right)^{\\prime }[/mathjaxinline],     * then use the formula   [mathjax]\\displaystyle \\frac{u^{\\prime }}{u} = \\left(\\ln (u)\\right)^{\\prime }[/mathjax]|   ---|---      and solve for [mathjaxinline]u'[/mathjaxinline].  Differentiation methods", "filename": "diff_8-tab10-text1.html", "title": "Differentiation methods"}

{"pageid": 212, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@sequential+block@approx_3-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@vertical+block@approx_3-tab10", "text": "[PDF Version](/static/pdf/newtonsmethod-summary.pdf)   **Newton's Method**  Given a function [mathjaxinline]\\ f(x)[/mathjaxinline], find [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline] such that [mathjaxinline]\\ f(x) = 0[/mathjaxinline].    1. Make a good guess [mathjaxinline]x_0[/mathjaxinline].     2. Call [mathjaxinline]x_1[/mathjaxinline] the [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline]-intercept of the tangent line through [mathjaxinline](x_0, f(x_0))[/mathjaxinline]. It has the formula   [mathjax]\\boxed { \\displaystyle x_1 = x_0 - \\frac{f(x_0)}{f'(x_0)}.}[/mathjax]| (5.59)   ---|---     3. Repeat. The general formula is   [mathjax]\\boxed { \\displaystyle x_{n+1} = x_n - \\frac{f(x_n)}{f'(x_n)}}[/mathjax]| (5.60)   ---|---      for [mathjaxinline]n=0,1,2, \\cdots[/mathjaxinline].  Summary", "filename": "approx_3-tab10-text1.html", "title": "Summary"}

{"pageid": 213, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@sequential+block@lim_1-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@vertical+block@lim_1-tab15", "text": "[PDF Version](/static/pdf/limitsintro-summary.pdf)   **Definitions of right-hand and left-hand limits**  ![See text below.](/static/images/u0lim1_leftright.svg)  Suppose [mathjaxinline]\\ f(x)[/mathjaxinline] gets really close to [mathjaxinline]R[/mathjaxinline] for values of [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline] that get really close to (but are not equal to) [mathjaxinline]a[/mathjaxinline] from the right. Then we say [mathjaxinline]R[/mathjaxinline] is the **right-hand limit** of the function [mathjaxinline]\\ f(x)[/mathjaxinline] as [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline] approaches [mathjaxinline]a[/mathjaxinline] from the right.  We write  [mathjaxinline]f(x) \\rightarrow R[/mathjaxinline] as [mathjaxinline]x \\rightarrow a^+[/mathjaxinline]   ---   or   [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle {\\lim _{x\\rightarrow \\mathbf{a^+}} f(x) = R}[/mathjaxinline].      If [mathjaxinline]\\ f(x)[/mathjaxinline] gets really close to [mathjaxinline]L[/mathjaxinline] for values of [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline] that get really close to (but are not equal to) [mathjaxinline]a[/mathjaxinline] from the left, we say that [mathjaxinline]L[/mathjaxinline] is the **left-hand limit** of the function [mathjaxinline]\\ f(x)[/mathjaxinline] as [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline] approaches [mathjaxinline]a[/mathjaxinline] from the left.  We write  [mathjaxinline]f(x) \\rightarrow L[/mathjaxinline] as [mathjaxinline]x \\rightarrow a^-[/mathjaxinline]   ---   or   [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle {\\lim _{x\\rightarrow \\mathbf{a^-}} f(x) = L}.[/mathjaxinline]      **Possible limit behaviors**  There are many possible limit behaviors.    * The right-hand and left-hand limits may both exist and be equal.     * The right-hand and left-hand limits may both exist, but may fail to be equal.     * A right- and/or left-hand limit could fail to exist due to blowing up to [mathjaxinline]\\pm \\infty[/mathjaxinline]. (Example: Consider the function [mathjaxinline]1/x[/mathjaxinline] near [mathjaxinline]x=0[/mathjaxinline].) In this case, we either say the limit blows up to infinity. We also say that the limit does not exist because [mathjaxinline]\\infty[/mathjaxinline] is not a real number!     * A right- and/or left-hand limit could fail to exist because it oscillates between many values and never settles down. In this case we say the limit does not exist.   **Definition of the Limit**   **The Limit in Words**  If a function [mathjaxinline]f(x)[/mathjaxinline] approaches some value [mathjaxinline]L[/mathjaxinline] as [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline] approaches [mathjaxinline]a[/mathjaxinline] from _both the right and the left_ , then **the limit** of [mathjaxinline]f(x)[/mathjaxinline] exists and equals [mathjaxinline]L[/mathjaxinline].  **The Limit in Symbols**  If  [mathjax]\\displaystyle {\\lim _{x\\rightarrow a^+} f(x)} = \\displaystyle {\\lim _{x\\rightarrow a^-} f(x)} = L[/mathjax]|   ---|---      then  [mathjax]\\displaystyle {\\lim _{x\\rightarrow a} f(x) = L}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      Alternatively,  [mathjax]f(x) \\rightarrow L \\quad \\mathrm{as} \\quad x\\rightarrow a.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      Remember that [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline] is approaching [mathjaxinline]a[/mathjaxinline] but does not equal [mathjaxinline]a[/mathjaxinline].  **The Limit Laws:**  Suppose [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle {\\lim _{x\\rightarrow a} f(x) = L}, \\qquad \\displaystyle {\\lim _{x\\rightarrow a} g(x) = M}.[/mathjaxinline]  Then we get the following Limit Laws:  Limit Law for Addition: |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle {\\lim _{x\\rightarrow a} \\left[f(x)+g(x)\\right] }[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]=[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]L+M[/mathjaxinline]   ---|---|---|---   Limit Law for Subtraction: |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle {\\lim _{x\\rightarrow a} \\left[f(x)-g(x)\\right] }[/mathjaxinline]| [mathjaxinline]=[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]L-M[/mathjaxinline]   Limit Law for Multiplication: |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle {\\lim _{x\\rightarrow a} \\left[f(x)\\cdot g(x)\\right] }[/mathjaxinline]| [mathjaxinline]=[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]L\\cdot M.[/mathjaxinline]      We also have part of the Limit Law for Division:  Limit Law for Division, Part 1: |  If [mathjaxinline]M\\ne 0[/mathjaxinline], then [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle {\\lim _{x\\rightarrow a} \\frac{f(x)}{g(x)} } = \\frac{L}{M}.[/mathjaxinline]   ---|---      We will discuss what happens when [mathjaxinline]M=0[/mathjaxinline] in a later section!  Summary", "filename": "lim_1-tab15-text1.html", "title": "Summary"}

{"pageid": 214, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@sequential+block@app_3-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@vertical+block@app_3-tab14", "text": "In the next video, we work out a question posed at the very beginning of this section:  What is the maximum vertical distance traversed during a zipline?  To answer this question, we actually answer a related question:  Given a mass on a weightless string, hold the two ends fixed. At what point will the mass settle?  The point at which it settles is the minimum [mathjaxinline]y[/mathjaxinline]-coordinate of the path traversed by a zipline rider. And this minimum [mathjaxinline]y[/mathjaxinline]-coordinate corresponds exactly to the point at which the rider has traversed the greatest (maximal) vertical drop. {"pageid": 219, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@sequential+block@study-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@vertical+block@study-tab5", "text": "**Best fit quadratic**  The best fit quadratic or best fit parabola to a function [mathjaxinline]\\ f(x)[/mathjaxinline] at the point [mathjaxinline]x=0[/mathjaxinline] is the quadratic function [mathjaxinline]q(x)[/mathjaxinline] whose value agree with the value of [mathjaxinline]\\ f[/mathjaxinline] at [mathjaxinline]x=0[/mathjaxinline], and whose first and second derivatives agree with the first and second derivatives of [mathjaxinline]\\ f[/mathjaxinline] at [mathjaxinline]x=0[/mathjaxinline], i.e.:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle f(0)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = q(0)[/mathjaxinline] |  | (7.12)   ---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle f'(0)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = q'(0)[/mathjaxinline] |  | (7.13)   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle f^{\\prime \\prime }(0)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = q^{\\prime \\prime }(0)[/mathjaxinline] |  | (7.14)  Best fit quadratic", "filename": "study-tab5-text2.html", "title": "Best fit quadratic"}

{"pageid": 220, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@sequential+block@lim_1-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@vertical+block@lim_1-tab10", "text": "**The Limit in Words**  If a function [mathjaxinline]f(x)[/mathjaxinline] approaches some value [mathjaxinline]L[/mathjaxinline] as [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline] approaches [mathjaxinline]a[/mathjaxinline] from _both the right and the left_ , then **the limit** of [mathjaxinline]f(x)[/mathjaxinline] exists and equals [mathjaxinline]L[/mathjaxinline].  **The Limit in Symbols**  If  [mathjax]\\displaystyle {\\lim _{x\\rightarrow a^+} f(x)} = \\displaystyle {\\lim _{x\\rightarrow a^-} f(x)} = L[/mathjax]|   ---|---      then  [mathjax]\\displaystyle {\\lim _{x\\rightarrow a} f(x) = L}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      Alternatively,  [mathjax]f(x) \\rightarrow L \\quad \\mathrm{as} \\quad x\\rightarrow a.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      Remember that [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline] is approaching [mathjaxinline]a[/mathjaxinline] but does not equal [mathjaxinline]a[/mathjaxinline].  ###  Formal definition of limit  Formally, the statement [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle {\\lim _{x\\rightarrow a} f(x) = L}[/mathjaxinline] is defined as:      For all [mathjaxinline]\\varepsilon >0,[/mathjaxinline] there exists some [mathjaxinline]\\delta > 0[/mathjaxinline] such that if [mathjaxinline]0 < |x-a| < \\delta ,[/mathjaxinline] then [mathjaxinline]|f(x)-L| < \\varepsilon .[/mathjaxinline]      As is traditional, we use the Greek letters [mathjaxinline]\\varepsilon[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\delta[/mathjaxinline].  Here is how one might understand that statement. The distance between two numbers [mathjaxinline]y[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]z[/mathjaxinline] is given by [mathjaxinline]|y-z|[/mathjaxinline]. Thus, the very last part of the definition is saying that the distance from [mathjaxinline]f(x)[/mathjaxinline] to [mathjaxinline]L[/mathjaxinline] is less than [mathjaxinline]\\varepsilon[/mathjaxinline]; one should think of [mathjaxinline]\\varepsilon[/mathjaxinline] as representing a small distance. This close distance occurs if [mathjaxinline]0<|x-a|<\\delta[/mathjaxinline]; that is, if [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline] is within some distance [mathjaxinline]\\delta[/mathjaxinline] from [mathjaxinline]a[/mathjaxinline], but not necessarily if that distance is 0 (we don't care about [mathjaxinline]x = a[/mathjaxinline] itself).  The \"for all\" and \"there exists\" clauses have to do with how small these distances need to get. We want [mathjaxinline]f(x)[/mathjaxinline] to eventually get arbitrarily close to [mathjaxinline]L[/mathjaxinline], so this statement needs to be satisfied no matter how small [mathjaxinline]\\varepsilon[/mathjaxinline] gets. Given any choice of [mathjaxinline]\\varepsilon[/mathjaxinline], we can satisfy the condition [mathjaxinline]|f(x) - L | < \\varepsilon[/mathjaxinline] as long as [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline] gets close enough to [mathjaxinline]a[/mathjaxinline]; the proximity required is measured by [mathjaxinline]\\delta[/mathjaxinline].  [Show](javascript: {return false;})  Definition of the limit", "filename": "lim_1-tab10-text1.html", "title": "Definition of the limit"}

{"pageid": 228, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@sequential+block@lim_2-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@vertical+block@lim_2-tab12", "text": "If [mathjaxinline]\\ f[/mathjaxinline] is a function which is continuous on the interval [mathjaxinline][a,b][/mathjaxinline], and [mathjaxinline]M[/mathjaxinline] lies between the values of [mathjaxinline]\\ f(a)[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\ f(b)[/mathjaxinline], then there is at least one point [mathjaxinline]c[/mathjaxinline] between [mathjaxinline]a[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]b[/mathjaxinline] such that [mathjaxinline]\\ f(c) = M.[/mathjaxinline]  (A function [mathjaxinline]\\ f[/mathjaxinline] is **continuous on a closed interval** [mathjaxinline][a,b][/mathjaxinline] if it is right-continuous at [mathjaxinline]a[/mathjaxinline], left-continuous at [mathjaxinline]b[/mathjaxinline], and continuous at all points between [mathjaxinline]a[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]b[/mathjaxinline].)  ###  What makes the Intermediate Value Theorem a deep result?  The Intermediate Value Theorem is profound because it takes information that is local by nature, and allows you to conclude a global result. Continuity at a point is local information, because it only requires knowledge of the function's behavior near that point. But somehow, if we know this fact at every point on an interval, then the Intermediate Value Theorem tells us something about the overall, or global behavior - namely, that the function has to take on a particular value, or its graph has to cross a certain line.  This is intimately tied in with the properties of the real number system. We could have the same definition of continuity for functions if we only worked with, say, the rational numbers (numbers which can be written as a fraction of integers), but the Intermediate Value Theorem would not work if that were the case. It is only when we move to the real numbers that the Intermediate Value Theorem holds true.  [Show](javascript: {return false;})  Intermediate Value Theorem", "filename": "lim_2-tab12-text1.html", "title": "Intermediate Value Theorem"}

{"pageid": 229, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@sequential+block@diff_1-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@vertical+block@diff_1-tab2", "text": "**Approximation of functions and derivatives**  The **tangent line** at [mathjaxinline]x=a[/mathjaxinline] is a good approximation for the **function** near [mathjaxinline]x=a[/mathjaxinline]. The **slope of the secant line** between [mathjaxinline]x=a[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]x=b[/mathjaxinline] is a good approximation for the **derivative** between [mathjaxinline]x=a[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]x=b[/mathjaxinline].  **Objectives**  At the end of this sequence, and after some practice, you should be able to:    * Understand where the **tangent line** is a good **linear approximation** to the function.     * Understand where the **average rate of change** is a good **linear approximation** to the **instantaneous rate of change**.     * **Approximate values of functions** given derivatives.     * **Approximate values of derivatives** given function data.     * Understand how **convexity/concavity** of the function affects the quality of the **linear approximation** , both qualitatively and quantitatively.   **Contents: 9 pages**  4 videos (13 minutes 1x speed) 14 questions  Objectives", "filename": "diff_1-tab2-text1.html", "title": "Objectives"}

{"pageid": 231, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@sequential+block@lim_3-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@vertical+block@lim_3-tab16", "text": "[PDF Version](/static/pdf/divisionlimitlaw-summary.pdf)   **Limit Law for Division**  If [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle {\\lim _{x\\rightarrow a} f(x) = L}[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle {\\lim _{x\\rightarrow a} g(x) = M},[/mathjaxinline] then:    * If [mathjaxinline]M \\ne 0,[/mathjaxinline] then [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle { \\lim _{x\\rightarrow a} \\frac{f(x)}{g(x)} = \\frac{L}{M}}[/mathjaxinline].     * If [mathjaxinline]M = 0[/mathjaxinline] but [mathjaxinline]L \\ne 0,[/mathjaxinline] then [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle {\\lim _{x\\rightarrow a} \\frac{f(x)}{g(x)}}[/mathjaxinline] does not exist.     * If both [mathjaxinline]M = 0[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]L = 0,[/mathjaxinline] then [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle {\\lim _{x\\rightarrow a} \\frac{f(x)}{g(x)}}[/mathjaxinline] might exist, or it might not exist. More work is necessary to determine whether the last type of limit exists, and what it is if it does exist.   Summary", "filename": "lim_3-tab16-text1.html", "title": "Summary"}

{"pageid": 234, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@sequential+block@study-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@vertical+block@study-tab4", "text": "**Domain and Range, Interval Notation**  Recall that the **domain** of a function [mathjaxinline]\\ f[/mathjaxinline] is the set of allowable input values. For instance, the domain of the function [mathjaxinline]\\ f(x) = 1/x[/mathjaxinline] is the set of all non-zero real numbers.  The **range** of [mathjaxinline]\\ f[/mathjaxinline] is the set of all possible output values. For instance, the range of the function [mathjaxinline]g(x) = x^2[/mathjaxinline] is the set of all real numbers that are non-negative.  We often use interval notation to express sets of numbers like domains and ranges. A **closed interval** , denoted [mathjaxinline][a,b][/mathjaxinline], is the set of numbers [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline] such that [mathjaxinline]a \\le x \\le b[/mathjaxinline].  An **open interval** , denoted [mathjaxinline](a,b)[/mathjaxinline], is the set of numbers [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline] such that [mathjaxinline]a < x < b[/mathjaxinline].  One can have a half-open, half-closed interval. For instance, [mathjaxinline][-1, 3)[/mathjaxinline] is the set of numbers [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline] such that [mathjaxinline]-1 \\le x <3[/mathjaxinline]. One can also use [mathjaxinline]\\pm \\infty[/mathjaxinline] as endpoints: [mathjaxinline](-\\infty , 0)[/mathjaxinline] is the set of numbers [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline] such that [mathjaxinline]-\\infty <x < 0[/mathjaxinline] (the set of negative numbers, in other words).  This notation using round parentheses for open intervals is not universal; many mathematicians use reversed square brackets instead. For instance, they would denote the interval [mathjaxinline]3 < x < 7[/mathjaxinline] as [mathjaxinline]]3,7[[/mathjaxinline] rather than [mathjaxinline](3,7)[/mathjaxinline]. In this course, however, we will stick to round parentheses for open intervals.  Domain and Range", "filename": "study-tab4-text8.html", "title": "Domain and Range"}

{"pageid": 235, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@sequential+block@der_1-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@vertical+block@der_1-tab3", "text": "Derivatives are all about rates of change. Rates of change", "filename": "der_1-tab3-text1.html", "title": "Rates of change"}

{"pageid": 236, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@sequential+block@logistics-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@vertical+block@logistics-tab2", "text": "Discover the derivative\u2014what it is, how to compute it, and when to apply it in solving real world problems. Part 1 of 3.  How does the final velocity on a zip line change when the starting point is raised or lowered by a matter of centimeters? What is the accuracy of a GPS position measurement? How fast should an airplane travel to minimize fuel consumption? The answers to all of these questions involve the derivative.  But what is the derivative? You will learn its mathematical notation, physical meaning, geometric interpretation, and be able to move fluently between these representations of the derivative. You will discover how to differentiate any function you can think up, and develop a powerful intuition to be able to sketch the graph of many functions. You will make linear and quadratic approximations of functions to simplify computations and gain intuition for system behavior. You will learn to maximize and minimize functions to optimize properties like cost, efficiency, energy, and power.  This course, in combination with 18.01.2x Calculus 1B: Integration, covers the AP Calculus AB curriculum. This course, in combination with 18.01.2x Calculus 1B: Integration and 18.01.3x Calculus 1C: Coordinate Systems and Infinite Series, covers the AP Calculus BC curriculum. {"pageid": 238, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@sequential+block@der_4-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@vertical+block@der_4-tab8", "text": "Suppose that [mathjaxinline]g(x) = kf(x)[/mathjaxinline] for all [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline], where [mathjaxinline]k[/mathjaxinline] is a constant. We know that  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle g'(x)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = \\lim _{\\Delta x \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{g(x+ \\Delta x) - g(x)}{\\Delta x}[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = \\lim _{\\Delta x \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{kf(x + \\Delta x) - kf(x)}{\\Delta x}[/mathjaxinline] |  |   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = \\lim _{\\Delta x \\rightarrow 0} k\\frac{f(x + \\Delta x) - f(x)}{\\Delta x}[/mathjaxinline] |  |   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =\\left( \\lim _{\\Delta x \\rightarrow 0} k\\right)\\left( \\ \\lim _{\\Delta x \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{f(x + \\Delta x) - f(x)}{\\Delta x}\\right).[/mathjaxinline] |  |      The first limit is just [mathjaxinline]k[/mathjaxinline], and the second limit is the definition of [mathjaxinline]\\ f'(x)[/mathjaxinline]. So we get [mathjaxinline]g'(x) = k f'(x)[/mathjaxinline].  Derivatives of constant multiples - proof", "filename": "der_4-tab8-text1.html", "title": "Derivatives of constant multiples - proof"}

{"pageid": 239, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@sequential+block@diff_3-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@vertical+block@diff_3-tab12", "text": "[PDF Version](/static/pdf/quotientrule-summary.pdf)   **The quotient rule**  If [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle h(x) = \\frac{f(x)}{g(x)}[/mathjaxinline] for all [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline], then  [mathjax]\\displaystyle h'(x) = \\frac{f'(x)g(x)-f(x)g'(x)}{g(x)^2}[/mathjax]|   ---|---      at all points where [mathjaxinline]\\ f[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]g[/mathjaxinline] are differentiable and [mathjaxinline]g(x) \\ne 0[/mathjaxinline].  **Derivatives of all trigonometric functions**  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle {\\frac{d}{dx}} \\sin x[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = \\cos x[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle {\\frac{d}{dx}} \\cos x[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = -\\sin x[/mathjaxinline] |  |   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle {\\frac{d}{dx}} \\tan x[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = \\frac{1}{\\cos ^2 x} = \\sec ^2 x[/mathjaxinline] |  |   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle {\\frac{d}{dx}} \\cot x[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = -\\frac{1}{\\sin ^2 x} = -\\csc ^2 x[/mathjaxinline] |  |   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle {\\frac{d}{dx}} \\sec x[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = \\frac{\\sin x}{\\cos ^2 x} = \\sec x \\tan x[/mathjaxinline] |  |   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle {\\frac{d}{dx}} \\csc x[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = -\\frac{\\cos x}{\\sin ^2 x} = -\\csc x \\cot x[/mathjaxinline] |  |  Summary", "filename": "diff_3-tab12-text1.html", "title": "Summary"}

{"pageid": 241, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@sequential+block@study-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@vertical+block@study-tab4", "text": "**Derivatives of Inverse Functions**  If [mathjaxinline]g[/mathjaxinline] is a (full or partial) inverse of a function [mathjaxinline]\\ f[/mathjaxinline], then  [mathjax]\\displaystyle {g'(x) = \\frac{1}{f'\\left(g(x)\\right)}}[/mathjax]|   ---|---      at all [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline] where [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle {f'\\left(g(x)\\right)}[/mathjaxinline] exists and is non-zero. {"pageid": 242, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@sequential+block@study-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@vertical+block@study-tab5", "text": "**Big-O notation**  A function [mathjaxinline]\\ f(x)[/mathjaxinline] is on the order [mathjaxinline]x^n[/mathjaxinline] near [mathjaxinline]x=0[/mathjaxinline], which is denoted using big \u201cO\" notation as [mathjaxinline]\\ f(x) = O(x^n)[/mathjaxinline] near [mathjaxinline]x=0[/mathjaxinline], if [mathjaxinline]\\left|f(x)\\right| \\leq k x^n[/mathjaxinline]. {"pageid": 243, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@sequential+block@der_2-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.1x+2T2022+type@vertical+block@der_2-tab2", "text": "**Geometric Interpretation of the Derivative: Tangent and Secant Lines**    * Instantaneous rate of change     * **Slope of the tangent line at that point**   **Objectives**  At the end of this lecture, and after some practice, you should be able to:    * Understand the correspondence between rates of change (both average and instantaneous) and **slopes of secant or tangent lines**.     * Be able to **estimate a derivative** of a function at a point, given its graph.     * Determine when a derivative does not exist.     * Use [mathjaxinline]\\Delta x[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\Delta y[/mathjaxinline] to denote small changes.   **Contents: 18 pages**  8 videos (21 minutes 1x speed) 25 questions  Objectives", "filename": "der_2-tab2-text1.html", "title": "Objectives"}
